<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IRA to Decide in November on Ceasefire Extension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Irish Republican Army (IRA)
will decide in November whether to extend their ceasefire declared
a week ago, according to a report from Dublin, the capital of the
Irish Republic today.
</P>
<P>
It said a meeting of the guerrillas' Army Convention would meet
to decide whether it was worth prolonging the truce.
</P>
<P>
The Sunday Independent reported that the IRA wanted Britain to
announce "confidence-building measures" including the release of
IRA prisoners, as a condition for extending the truce.
</P>
<P>
Other measures according to the paper, are the transfer of IRA
prisoners held in jails on the British mainland to prisons in the
Irish Republic and Northern Ireland so they can be closer to their
families.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the IRA also wanted Britain to announce the
departure of some of its 18,000 troops from Northern Ireland, who
have been in the province for 28 years backing up police patrols
against attacks from the IRA.
</P>
<P>
It is generally believed that the IRA's "total cessation" was
a temporary measure linked to demands for concessions from
Britain's new Labor government.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, many members of the IRA, which has
fount for three decades to oust Britain from Northern Ireland,
were unhappy at declaring the truce that will admit Sinn Fein to
Belfast peace talks which start in September.
</P>
<P>
The Independent quoted Irish police intelligence as saying that
it believed up to 15 percent of the IRA's leadership opposed the
ceasefire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
