<HEADLINE> Anti-Taliban Alliance Issues Ultimatum to Taliban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Forces opposing the Afghan
Islamic Taliban militia today sent out an ultimatum to the
militia, demanding their withdrawal from the capital city of Kabul
in 24 hours, informed sources said.
</P>
<P>
The anti-Taliban alliance warned in the ultimatum if the
Taliban failed to meet the deadline, they would launch a
three-pronged full-scale assault against the Taliban
simultaneously from the west, north and east sides of Kabul, said
the sources in Peshawar, a major city in northwestern Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, who have controlled Kabul since September last
year, have so far made no comment on the deadline set by the
opposition alliance, whose forces have advanced to within the
rocket range of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
Over the past three days, the anti-Taliban forces under the
commander of Ahmad Masood, former Afghan military chief, have kept
military pressure on Kabul with jets and artillery bombardments
while calling for a Taliban pullout from the beleaguered capital.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued Saturday by the United Islamic Front for the
Salvation of Afghanistan, the name of the anti-Taliban alliance,
said that only when the Taliban "demilitarize Kabul" could issues
including a cease-fire and exchange of prisoners be negotiated.
</P>
<P>
However, the opposition's call has reportedly been rejected by
the Taliban, who now control about two thirds of the Afghan
territory, saying that they would defend Kabul at all costs.
</P>
<P>
The atmosphere in Kabul has been tense as the Taliban have
brought in hundreds of young fighters from southern provinces and
reportedly arrested hundreds of people suspected to be opposition
fighters who were said to have infiltrated into the capital.
</P>
<P>
Several diplomatic missions at Kabul have called back their
diplomats because of uncertainty prevailing in and around Kabul
due to the fresh fighting. Over 60 diplomats of various countries
from Kabul arrived in Peshawar bordering Afghanistan Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
