<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Opposes Timing of New Housing Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu said today he opposed going ahead now with the Jewish
housing project at Ras el Amud in East Jerusalem, which threatens
to scuttle the Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the weekly cabinet meeting today, Netanyahu cited
the bad timing as the reason for his objection to the housing
project. He said Israel was building in Jerusalem, including at
Har Homa, in efforts to "spread our sovereignty over all parts of
the city and strengthen our security presence."
</P>
<P>
The expansion of Jewish settlement in Har Homa in East
Jerusalem, where the Palestinians want as their future capital,
has crippled the Middle East peace process since March.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said that despite the government's opposition to the
housing project at this time, this should not be interpreted as a
change in its policy on Jerusalem, which Israel claims as its
eternal capital.
</P>
<P>
He added that Attorney-General Elyakim Rubinstein is examining
whether the government could block the American real estate
developer Irving Moskowitz from carrying out the housing project
at this time.
</P>
<P>
Most cabinet ministers voiced their support to Netanyahu and
criticized the Jerusalem municipality for having not consulted
with the government in authorizing the controversial housing
project.
</P>
<P>
But several rightist ministers, including Transportation
Minister Yitzhak Levy and Agriculture Minister Rafael Eitan,
contended that the project should be carried out without delay.
</P>
<P>
Levy said that timing was a "poor excuse which could not be
used to cover every subject." He said the Ras el Amud project
would constitute the Jewish claim over Mount of Olives area in the
heart of East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Despite warnings from the Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
and the objection of the Israeli government, the American real
estate developer vowed today to push through his plan and begin
soon the construction work at the Ras el Amud Arab neighborhood,
where he intended to build about 70 housing units for Jews.
</P>
<P>
Interviewed by Israeli Army Radio, Moskowitz expressed anger
at the statements by Jerusalem municipality and Netanyahu's
office declaring that he had decided to delay the housing
project. He argued that the Ras el Amud was not a political
question, but one concerning the right of a private owner to
build on his own property.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that since Israel is a democratic country, nothing
could block his project for any reasons.
</P>
<P>
Backtracking from his earlier hardline position, Likud's
Jerusalem Major Ehud Olmert confirmed today that Moskowitz still
needed further technical approval for going ahead with the
housing project. But he denied he had changed his position in
favor of carrying out the project, adding he did not know how the
Netanyahu government could block it since Moskowitz had obtained
legal permits.
</P>
<P>
The Ras el Amud housing project has revived the old dispute
between Israel and the PNA over the status of Jerusalem at an
unwanted time when the peace process has been deadlocked for four
months.
</P>
<P>
Israeli has claimed whole Jerusalem as the indivisible and
eternal capital of the Jewish state, while the PNA hopes to
establish a Palestinian state with the occupied East Jerusalem as
its capital.
</P>
<P>
Under the Oslo accords, the issue of Jerusalem should be
settled through negotiations in the final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
In tough reactions to the Ras el Amud project, PNA officials
have repeatedly warned that implementation of the plan would lead
to violent confrontation and kill the moribund peace process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
