<DOCNO> XIE19970728.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-27 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Velayati on Ties with U.S., EU and Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar
Velayati today dismissed earlier reports that Saudi Arabia had
tried to mediate between Tehran and Washington.
</P>
<P>
"No one has brought us any messages (from the U.S.). The
message delivered by the recent envoy of Saudi King was about
bilateral relations and Organization of the Islamic Conference,"
Velayati said in an interview with the Persian-language daily
Kayhan.
</P>
<P>
Arab media earlier reported that King Fahd's envoy Abdul Aziz
Al-Khwather, during his meeting with Iranian President Hashemi
Rafsanjani only July 1, expressed Riyadh's willingness to mediate
between Iran and the U.S.
</P>
<P>
However, Velayati said the U.S. did send signals to Iran and
its messages were "delivered through their interest section at
the Swiss Embassy in Tehran."
</P>
<P>
The two countries cut off their diplomatic relations soon after
the victory of Iran's Islamic Revolution.
</P>
<P>
On relations with European countries, Velayati said Iran did
not want to harm its ties with the European Union, but the
Europeans should have to honor the dignity of Iran, a precondition
set by Iran's Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei last April.
</P>
<P>
"We do not plan to disrupt our ties with Europe, but the
principle of dignity, as was said by the leader, is one of our
requirements," Velayati said.
</P>
<P>
The EU member countries recalled their ambassadors from Tehran
after a German court implicated Iranian leaders in the murder of
four Kurdish dissidents in Berlin in 1992.
</P>
<P>
On April 30, Khamenei retaliated by instructing Iranian
government not to allow the German ambassador to return to
Tehran. He said that other EU ambassadors could return but Iran
should not rush to send its ambassadors back to Europe.
</P>
<P>
Velayati said in the interview that Iran was engaged in
dialogue with Italy and Germany, but the results were not
satisfactory.
</P>
<P>
"Our embassies are open in both countries (Italy and
Germany). Our discussions are continuing as before and plenty of
dialogue have been held, but they have not yet to reach the point
as defined by the leader," he added.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the newly formed secularist government headed by
Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz in Turkey, Velayati said this
government is doomed to be weak.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister had criticized Turkey's top military brass
for putting pressure on Necmettin Erbakan, the country's first
Islamist prime minister and working for his oust.
</P>
<P>
"Pressures were brought upon to force Mr. Erbakan out of power
just because he is a Muslim. This all shows how Muslims are under
pressure around the world,+ he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
