<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TUC, CBI to Hold Talks on Recognition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 27 (Xinhua) -- A meeting between business and
trades union leaders last week could lead to a deal over the Labor
government plan to give workers a legal right to union
recognition, the British newspaper, the Observer said today.
</P>
<P>
The talks appear to have softened the Confederation of British
Industry's (CBI) pre-election hostility to giving unions the right
to be heard where they speak for more than half the "relevant
workforce".
</P>
<P>
A spokesman from CBI said: "We remain opposed to the policy in
principle, but we now accept it will happen and we have to talk
sensibly to the unions, to help our understanding and get the best
possible outcome."
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month John Monks, the general secretary of the
Trade Union of Congress (TUC) told a CBI audience in a gathering
that he accepted that the unions must meet the employers' genuine
concerns about the plans, on which the Government is pledged to
legislate next year.
</P>
<P>
The two sides are discussing guidelines to define the term
"relevant workforce" and pin down how the law should be enforced,
according to the Observer.
</P>
<P>
Among those present at the meeting were CBI director-general
Adair Turner, its president Sir Colin Marshall and Tony Greener,
chairman of drinks giant Guinness.
</P>
<P>
Monks headed the unions side, which included Rodney
Bickerstaffe of public service union Unison, John Edmonds of the
GMB general union, Ken Jackson of engineering union AEEU, and Tony
Dubbins of the GPMU printers.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was the second since the Labor came to power. The
Observer said it showed how times have changed. "The participants
dined on roast loin of pork in a prune and sloe gin sauce," it
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
