<HEADLINE> Jordan: Settlements Should Be Final Status Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 27 (Xinhua) - The Jewish settlements in Arab East
Jerusalem should be an issue to be discussed at the
Palestinian-Israeli final status talks, Jordanian Foreign Minister
Fayez Tarawneh said today.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh made the remarks to the press after holding talks
here with visiting Mahmoud Abbas, top Palestinian peace negotiator
and Secretary General of the Executive Committee of the
Palestinian Liberation Organization (PLO), Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
Jordan Saturday officially condemned the authorization by
Israeli Jerusalem Municipality of a United States millionaire to
build 70 Jewish homes in the heart of the Arab neighborhood
of Ras El Amud.
</P>
<P>
This is the first reaction of Jordanian government saying that
the new settlement plans would further aggravate tension between
Israel and the Palestinians which started when Israeli government
began to build the first settlement Arab East Jerusalem in March
this year.
</P>
<P>
Jordan had noticed that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu had a positive stand on the Amud settlement and also
learnt that the settlement would be postponed, he said, adding
that settlements were final status issue and should not be an
unilateral action.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East peace process has been deadlocked since
February when Israeli government decided to build the
settlements. Talks to salvage the process have been mediated by
the international community, but none of them have produced any
positive results. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
