<HEADLINE> Jordan Dismisses Reported Tripartite Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 27 (Xinhua) - Jordan's Foreign Minister Fayez
Tarawneh here today dismissed as speculation a reported tripartite
meeting among Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak and Jordan's King Hussein.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister made the clarification after talks with
Mahmoud Abbas, top Palestinian peace negotiator and Secretary
General of the Executive Committee of the Palestinian Liberation
Organization (PLO), Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
Peace coordination among Jordan, the Palestinians and Egypt
was now at its highest level, but a tripartite meeting was just a
"speculation," said Tarawneh.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, efforts were underway for Jordan to foster
closer relations with the Palestinians, the minister said, adding
bilateral talks began soon after Abbas arrived in Amman Saturday
on a brief visit.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Jordanian consultation came after the Israeli
Jerusalem Municipality permitted a U.S. Jewish millionaire to
build 70 housing units in the heart of the Arab neighborhood of
Ras el Amud in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has condemned this move, the second in four months. The
Israeli decision in March on expanding Jewish settlement in Har
Homa put the Middle East peace process to a standstill.
</P>
<P>
Efforts to revive the crippled peace talks between the
Palestinian and Israelis have so far been to no avail.
</P>
<P>
Jordan helped mediate in January this year the Hebron accord
setting forth the Israeli pullout from Hebron and West Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
