<HEADLINE> Palestinians Continue Voicing Opposition To New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian officials today
are continuing their strong opposition to Israel's decision to
establish a new Jewish settlement in the heart of an Arab
neighborhood in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Ziyad Abu Zayad, Jerusalem member of the legislative
Palestinian Council, warned of disastrous consequences if the
construction goes ahead.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Municipality approved Thursday the construction
of more than 100 housing units in the Ras El-Amud section of the
Mount of Olive, and Arab neighborhood. The decision triggered a
wave of furious condemnation from the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
Zayad told Israel Radio that the settlement means that there
will be continuous provocations and fictions which will make
troubles and problems every day.
</P>
<P>
He said that Jerusalem is one of the issues of upmost
importance in the final-status talks. But now Israel wants to
change the fact on the ground in Jerusalem. If such a thing is
allowed, he noted, "there will be no chance for the future talks
because of fear and suspicion on both sides."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on press reports that Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu would try his best to block the construction, Zayad
expressed doubt about his sincerity, saying that this is not
the first time that this government and this prime minister
say something and do the opposite.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, he said: "I hope sincerely that this time he
will stand by his words and will not allow Ras El-Amud project."
</P>
<P>
Nabil Sha'ath, Palestinian negotiator, expressed welcome to
Netanyahu's statement of opposition to the new settlement. But
he noted that the statements made by Netanyahu and other
government ministers would be translated into an act to cancel
all settlement constructions altogether.
</P>
<P>
Faisal Husseini, PLO Executive Committee member, and officials
from the Palestinian National and Islamic Committee to Confront
Settlements held an urgent meeting in East Jerusalem this evening
to discuss ways and means to cope with the Jerusalem
Municipality's decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
