<DOCNO> XIE19970728.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-27 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Velayati Rejects Calls to Cut off Ties with Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar
Velayati has rejected appeals from the hardline camp that Tehran
must completely sever its relations with Cairo.
</P>
<P>
"We can not forget the Egyptian nation and the great Islamic
country of Egypt," Velayati said in an interview appearing on the
Persian-language evening newspaper Kayhan.
</P>
<P>
The two countries resumed diplomatic ties in 1991 after a lapse
of 12 years, at a lower level of interest sections. However, their
relations again soured in 1992 after Cairo accused Tehran of
supporting Egypt's underground Islamic movement with money and
weapons.
</P>
<P>
Velayati said Egypt's position has changed over the past three
years - it has been distancing itself from the position it adopted
in the Camp David Accord hammering out peace between Egypt and
Israel.
</P>
<P>
The accord, signed by then Egyptian President Anwar Sadat and
Israeli Prime Minister Menachem Begin on March 26, 1979, brought
to an end 30 years of hostilities between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Velayati visit Egypt last May to hold talks with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak and deliver Iranian President Hashemi
Rafsanjani's invitation to his Egyptian counterpart for an official
visit.
</P>
<P>
Velayati, who has been foreign minister for 16 years, brushed
aside criticisms of his ministry's "ignoring Islamists in Egypt"
while nurturing ties with Cairo.
</P>
<P>
"it is incumbent upon us, as a government, that we would not
interfere in the internal affairs of other countries." Velayati
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
