<HEADLINE> Sex Education Called for in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 27 (Xinhua) -- A comprehensive sex education,
especially for young people, has been suggested as a measure to
curb the high incidence of unsafe abortion in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Unsafe abortion contributes to about 50 percent of Nigeria's
nearly 75,000 annual maternal deaths, according to a communique
released at a workshop on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
A wide range of family planning options would drastically
reduce unsafe abortion, said participants, quoted by local media
today.
</P>
<P>
While calling for family planning information and services to
men, they said the abortion law, which was full of defects,
should be reformed to protect women from unskilled personnel and
reduce maternal morbidity and mortality.
</P>
<P>
The workshop was organized by a local non-government
organization, the Campaign Against Unwanted Pregnancies, in Ogun
State, western Nigeria.  
</P>
</TEXT>
