<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plane Crash Kills 9, Injures 57 in Belgian Air Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Nine people including a
22-month-old girl were killed and 57 injured when a biplane
crashed during an air show in the Belgian town of Ostend late on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Five of the dead are Belgian and two are from France. The pilot
who was also killed in the incident is from Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Of the injured who were hurried to local hospitals by
helicopters, 10 were badly hurt and several were in critical
conditions, local television reported on Sunday. Doctors of local
hospitals feared that the death toll might still rise.
</P>
<P>
The pilot of a Falco XT-300, which belonged to the Jordanian
air force, apparently lost control while doing a looping stunt and
the plane plunged into a Red Cross tent some 150 meters away from
spectators, some of whom were sprayed with burning kerosene, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Ostend is a seaside resort by the North Sea.
</P>
<P>
The Ostend air show has been staged five times and Saturday's
crash was the first.
</P>
<P>
Aviation experts and Falco engineers from Germany are
collecting parts of the crashed plane which had been specially
designed and manufactured for aerial stunts and the biplane was
made of light-weight composite materials.
</P>
<P>
The experts will also be helped by some video recordings shot
by photography amateurs on the spot.
</P>
<P>
Belgian Interior Minister Vande Lanotte, who accompanied the
Belgian king and queen as well as Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene
on a condolence trip to Ostend Sunday morning, said that
investigation was underway and it was too early to attribute the
cause of the crash to either human error or mechanical failure,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
The investigation may take some time to come up with any
conclusion. The crash of a Belgian air force C-130 transporter at
Eindhoven last year took two weeks to produce a preliminary report
on the accident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
