<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are Business briefs
from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The Arab Investment Company said it recorded
27.7 million dollars in profits last year, a jump of 9.4 million
dollars compared to 1995, a statement by the Riyadh-based company
showed today.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the company decided to increase its
capital from 300 million dollars to 400 million dollars in
the future.
</P>
<P>
Until the end of last year, the financial institute's deposits
stood at 824 million U.S. dollars, while the credit facilities
reached 495 million U.S. dollars last year in comparison to 410
million U.S. dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The company was established by 15 Arab countries in 1974 with
the major aim of carrying out investments projects and taking
part in financing schemes in the private and public sectors.
</P>
<P>
It now owns 34 projects in the public and private sectors
in 12 Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Jordanian-Palestinian Technical Committee met
here today to put forth a joint mechanism to facilitate the goods
inflows between Jordan and the Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
Both sides were keen to boost trade exchanges, said Jordanian
Minister of Trade, Industry and Supply Hani Mulki after holding
talks with Hany Salami, an adviser to Palestinian President Yasser
 Arafat.
</P>
<P>
The trade volume between Jordan and the Palestinians reached
21 million U.S. dollars in the first eight months of 1996,
compared to 20 million dollars in the whole year of 1995,
according to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates' oil
output reached 117.3 million tonnes in 1996 while that of natural
gas topped 35 billion cubic meters, said a latest energy report
here today.
</P>
<P>
These indicate a 3.2 percent increase in oil output as against
113.7 million tonnes in 1995, and a 17 percent hike in natural gas
as compared with 29.9 billion cubic meters in the previous year,
said the Statistical Review of World Energy 1997.
</P>
<P>
As the world's top seven oil producers, the UAE has the world's
fourth largest proven oil reserves of 97.8 billion barrels by the
end of 1996, or 9.4 percent of the world's total of 1036.9 billion
barrels.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- A total of 13 Arab countries out of the
22-member Arab League recorded a rise in their annual growth rates
of 4 to 7 percent in 1996, an economic report said today.
</P>
<P>
An annual report published by the Kuwait-based Arab
Corporation for Investment Guarantee, said countries achieved
growth rates were Mauritania by 7 percent, Tunisia 6.9
percent, Jordan 5.2 percent, Egypt 4.9 percent, Sudan 4.7
percent, Yemen 4.5 percent and Algeria 4.4 percent,
</P>
<P>
Six other countries including Lebanon, Morocco and four oil
exporting Gulf Arab countries such as Saudi Arabia, Kuwait,
Oman and the United Arab Emirates achieved a growth rate of
4 percent each, the report said.
</P>
<P>
However, Palestine recorded a minus 3 percent growth rate, the
report pointed out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
