<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Canadians Think Crime Is Rising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Most Canadians still live in fear
despite studies showing drops in violent crime across the country,
said a report today.
</P>
<P>
The latest poll, conducted for CTV News by the Angus Reid
group, indicated most Canadians, especially those in western
Canada, believe crime in their communities is on the rise.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-nine of those surveyed said they believe crime in their
community has gone up in the past five years. Thirty percent think
the rate of crime hasn't changed, and only 8 percent believe that
crime is going down.
</P>
<P>
The anxiety about crime seems to grow in intensity in the four
western provinces. Seventy-eight percent in British Columbia said
they believe crime is on the rise, and 30 percent said there had
been a "great increase" in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
In addition, crime ranks atop the list of concern for people in
the four provinces, while unemployment is the chief concern for
those in Ontario, Quebec and the Atlantic provinces.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-one percent of those surveyed said they fear being a
victim of crime in their own community, with 5 percent having a
"great deal" of fear they will be a victim.
</P>
<P>
An earlier government report said violent crime in Canada is
decreasing, and the murder rate was at a 25-year low.
</P>
<P>
According to John Wright, senior vice-president of the Angus
Reid Group, fear remains high because media reports of crime,
especially violent crime, continue to bombard the public.
</P>
<P>
"People are sensitized to it because it makes news, because
it's in their face every single day," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
