<HEADLINE> Old Soldiers Meet To Mark Army's Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 28 (Xinhua) -- A group of ranking army officers
and ex-soldiers who fought against the Kuomintang regime and the
Japanese invaders from the 1920s to 1940s held a panel discussion
in Beijing today to mark the 70th anniversary of the founding of
the Communist-led armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Those participating in today's gathering spoke highly of the
army's successes since it came into being on August 1, 1927, when
Communists led an uprising against the Kuomintang warlords and set
up bases in some mountainous areas for armed struggle against the
reactionary Kuomintang regime.
</P>
<P>
General Liu Huaqing made a speech on behalf of the Central
Military Commission and the headquarters of the People's
Liberation Army and expressed his respect for all the old soldiers
who have fought for the nation's independence and liberation.
</P>
<P>
Liu, who is a member of the Standing Committee of the Political
Bureau of the Communist Party of China Central Committee and
vice-chairman of the Central Military Commission, said that the
present duties of the army are to sum up the past experiences and
improve its work so as to provide a powerful security guarantee
for the country's reform, opening-up and modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
He urged everyone present to follow and promote Mao Zedong
Thought and Deng Xiaoping's theory of building socialism with
Chinese characteristics to keep the army on the correct
development path.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party of China (CPC) has absolute leadership over
the army, and army act in harmony, ideologically and politically,
with the CPC Central Committee with Jiang Zemin at the core, the
general said. 
</P>
