<HEADLINE> China to Adopt Law on Donations  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 28 (Xinhua) -- China is drafting a law on
donations to promote the healthy development of its fledging
public welfare system, according to a top Chinese legislator.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Chunsheng, deputy director of the Commission of
Legislative Affairs under the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress (NPC), told a symposium here last week that the
draft law on donations was created to keep the country's
increasing amount of monetary gifts under control.
</P>
<P>
"The law is expected to be adopted to encourage and guide
various kinds of donations for public welfare, and to standardize
the activities of donations, money raising and use of donations,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
A draft law was made during a symposium on the donation law
held from July 22-25. The meeting was sponsored by the Commission
of the Legislative Affairs under the NPC Standing Committee, the
NPC Overseas Chinese Affair Committee and the China Charity
Federation (CCF).
</P>
<P>
However, the legislative affairs officials believed that the
legal procedure for the donations law should be clarified, and
there is a need to consult with the public, since this is the
first law of its kind in the country and will be of interest to
the masses.
</P>
</TEXT>
