<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Meteorological Satellite Sends Back Clear Photos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The Fengyun 2 meteorological
satellite is in stable condition and has sent back many clear
photos of the earth since it was launched in June 10, according to
the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
The pictures have been shown as part of the weather forecast
broadcast by China Central Television (CCTV). The satellite will
be soon turned over to the State Meteorological Administration for
its use.
</P>
<P>
The key sounding device used by the satellite is the
multi-channel scanning radiometer produced by the Institute of
Technical Physics in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Scientists say that the radiometer can monitor the dynamic
meteorological changes above China and neighboring countries in a
synchronous orbit 35,800 kilometers above earth. It also can
provide timely meteorological information that is valuable for
short- and long-term weather forecasts and for natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
The radiometer is the result of 15 years' work by scientists
from the Institute of Technical Physics and five other institutes
and factories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970728.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gender Discrimination Also Seen in Nepali Media </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The age-old discrimination
against women exists not only in other sectors but also in
communications, Nepali Minister for Information and Communications
Jhalanath Khanal said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Women constitute 12 percent of the journalists working in the
official media, but the percentage fells down to eight if female
journalists working in the private sector are included in the
calculation, Khanal told a seminar entitled Communications for
Equality and Solidarity, co-sponsored by the Women Journalists
Group.
</P>
<P>
The minister stressed that political commitment alone is not
enough to increase women's participation in the media, there
should be laws to encourage this, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Former Nepali Foreign Minister Prakash Chandra Lohani said
scholarships should be awarded and incentives should be given to
women to take up journalism.
</P>
<P>
Sociologist Krishna Bahadur Bhattachan said women hesitate to
join the media because of negative attitude, male domination,
political prejudice and gender discrimination.
</P>
<P>
President of the Federation of Nepalese Journalists Harihar
Birahi stressed the need for female journalists to delve into the
basic problems of the country without getting bogged down on
women's problems only, the reports said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
