<HEADLINE> S. Africa, Nigeria to Resolve Diplomatic Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 28 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela and Nigeria's top leader Sani Abacha have been in
regular contact and would resolve the latest diplomatic row
between them, presidential aide Parks Mankahlana said today.
</P>
<P>
The tension follows Nigerian Information Minister Walter
Ofonagoro's slating of Mandela as the "black head of a white
country", and his claims that South Africa is spearheading
anti-Nigerian propaganda.
</P>
<P>
In a diplomatic note to Nigeria's Foreign Affairs Ministry
last week, the South African government objected to Ofongagoro's
"serious and unprovoked attack" and asked for "immediate
clarification".
</P>
<P>
The note said, "an apology to President Mandela and the people
of South Africa would seem reasonable."
</P>
<P>
However, no apology has yet been forthcoming, South African
government officials said.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time the South African government has
requested an apology from Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Two years ago, Abacha described Mandela as "someone who has
lost touch with realities" after his 27 years in jail. The
military leader was asked to apologize for the statement after
both the ambassadors in Lagos and Pretoria were recalled.
</P>
<P>
The relations between the two countries deteriorated in 1995
following Mandela's hardline approach against Abacha's government
for executing Ken Saro Wiwa and other activists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
