<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Largest Seismology Exhibition Takes Place in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Beijingers worried about what to
do in the event of an earthquake can ease their fears at China's
largest-ever seismology exhibition, currently on show at the
Geological Museum in the capital city.
</P>
<P>
Computer images vividly illustrate facts about earthquakes and
important safety tips in case a quake hits. The exhibition will go
on tour nationwide after its run in Beijing closes on August 28.
</P>
<P>
Chen Zangli, director of the State Seismology Bureau, said that
China has frequent seismic activity; about 29 provinces,
municipalities, and autonomous regions have been hit with
earthquakes in this century with a magnitude of more than six on
the Richter Scale.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that in 1988 China entered its fifth period of
seismic activity, which will continue into the next
century. During this time, precautions against earthquakes will be
jointly taken by governments, special departments, and the Chinese
people, he said.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition is co-sponsored by the State Seismology Bureau,
the State Education Commission, the State Science and Technology
Commission, the Ministry of Geology and Mineral Resources and the
People's Insurance Company.
</P>
</TEXT>
