<HEADLINE> China Urges EU to Avoid Confrontation on Human Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PETALING JAYA, Malaysia, July 28 (Xinhua) -- China today urged
the European Union (EU) to avoid confrontation on the question of
human rights.
</P>
<P>
Meeting with Luxembourg Foreign Minister Jacques Poos here,
Chinese Vice Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen said
confrontation does not help with mutual understanding and is
detrimental to both sides, a Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that on human rights, EU countries stand for dialogue
 instead of confrontation, and China welcomes and supports such a
stand.
</P>
<P>
Poos said the EU is ready to seek dialogue and hopes to
increase dialogue and cooperation with China in international
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Qian noted China and the EU countries have maintained frequent
contacts, high-level visits have been fruitful and economic and
trade relations have been growing.
</P>
<P>
"We believe relations between the two sides are good on the
whole," Qian said.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers spoke highly of relations between China and
Luxembourg and pledged to continue maintaining and expanding this
mutually beneficial relationship.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers are here attending the two-day ASEAN Post
Ministerial Conference which began today.  
