<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Chinese Maps on Display in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Well-known ancient Chinese maps
which date as early as 860 years ago are being displayed in a
unique exhibition which opened here today.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition named "History Through Maps" in the Hong Kong
Museum is jointly organized by the Hong Kong Provisional Urban
Council (PUC) and the National Library of China.
</P>
<P>
Among the over 70 ancient maps on display are 29 pieces from
extremely rare cartographic documents on loan from the National
Library, more than 30 from the collection of famed Hong Kong
collector Tam Siu-cheung and the rest are lent by the Hong Kong
University, Hong Kong Museum of Art, Public Records Office and the
Hong Kong Museum of History.
</P>
<P>
The exhibits are of seven categories -- world maps and general
maps of China, maps of administrative divisions, maps of
metropolis, maps of scenic spots, maps of military significance,
maps of economic undertakings and maps of Guangdong.
</P>
<P>
Among those on display are the impressive Pingjiangtu, which is
the first and largest map of a Chinese city, and famous Yujitu
dated 1136 AD, which is the oldest map using lattice grid with
scale.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that most traditional ancient Chinese maps were
presented either pictorially in the style of Chinese landscape
painting with little concern of scale, or more scientifically in
the form of Jilihuafang with the land drawn to a grid scale of a
certain li (a Chinese unit of length which is approximately
equivalent to 0.5 kilometers) to each division.
</P>
<P>
The style was brought to Europe via Arabia about 700 years ago
by traders and commissioners, which directly prompted the
breakthroughs in European cartography.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970728.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Central Bank Cuts Borrowing Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the Philippines
said today it will reduce its overnight borrowing rate from 25
percent to 22 percent Tuesday with the country's currency peso
stabilizing in the currency market.
</P>
<P>
The local ABS-CBN television quoted central bank officials as
saying that the bank expected the peso to stabilize against the
U.S. dollar in the coming days after weeks of turmoil in the
foreign currency market.
</P>
<P>
This is the third time for the Central Bank to cut its key
borrowing rate since the peso was allowed to move in a wider range
in a de facto depreciation on July 11.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the fresh reduction in interest rate will help
buoy the local bourse which has been bearish for nearly two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank spiraled up its overnight borrowing rate to a
four-year high of 32 percent early this month in a bid to fend the
peso off the fierce speculative attacks.
</P>
<P>
The bank has indicated that it will correspondingly reduce
hefty interest rates as the foreign currency market stabilizes.
Economists have warned that continued high interest rates will
slow down the economy.
</P>
<P>
The peso is pegged at 28.47 against one U.S. dollar today at
the Philippine Dealing System, the country's electronic currencies
exchange. This represented a significant recovery of the peso from
its lowest level of 29.45 to one dollar recorded soon after the
announcement of the effective devaluation.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson has projected earlier the
average peso-dollar exchange rate to rebound to between 26.50
pesos and 27.00 pesos by the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
But economists said it is very difficult for the peso to return
to the level of 26.40 pesos to one dollar kept by the Central Bank
prior to its depreciation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
