<HEADLINE> South Korea's Current Account to Improve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 28 (Xinhua) -- While the nation's current deficit
surpassed the 10 billion U.S. dollars mark in the first half of
this year, South Korea's central bank expects the current account
to be in better situation by year-end.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's current-account deficit totaled 10.28 billion
U.S.dollars for the first half of this year, up 4.7 percent from
last year, the Bank of Korea said today.
</P>
<P>
The unrequited transfer deficit slid from 420 million
U.S. dollars to 330 million U.S. dollars, but the visible and
invisible trade deficits rose from 5.64 billion U.S. dollars and
3.76 billion U.S. dollars to 6.06 billion and 3.9 billion,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The central bank predicted the current-account deficit for the
whole year would be 17 billion U.S. dollars against last year's
23.72 billion.
</P>
<P>
Kwak Tong-joon, senior research economist of the central bank,
said the trade deficit for the latter half of the year would be
less than one billion U.S. dollars, as the nation's economic
slowdown put brakes on import growth while exports continue to
rise.
</P>
<P>
In June, exports jumped 8.8 percent and imports rose 4.5
percent resulting in a trade surplus of 260 million U.S. dollars
for the first time since December 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
