<HEADLINE> Thomson, Siemens to Jointly Develop Air Traffic Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Thomson-CSF and Siemens, two
European electronic giants, will be able to jointly develop air
traffic management under the approval by the European Commission
(EC).
</P>
<P>
The EC, the executive body of the European Union, said in a
press release today that it has approved a joint-venture agreement
between the two groups.
</P>
<P>
The two groups are to develop part of the airport turnkey
system known as the Airsys.
</P>
<P>
Air traffic management covers all the ground systems and
equipment needed to provide full air space surveillance and
control facilities to ensure full safety to civil air transport
activities.
</P>
<P>
Though market demand slowed down in the past few years after a
period of strong growth during the 1980s and early 1990s, it is
still a growing market due to the fact that many countries are
modernizing and will modernize and standardize their air traffic
management on the basis of emerging new technologies. 
</P>
