<HEADLINE> E. Africa States to Join Hands Against Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda are
scheduled to have an east African regional meeting to map out a
strategy in order to stop smuggling on their common borders and
on Lake Victoria, local press said today.
</P>
<P>
The weekly paper, "The East African", said that the meeting to
be held this week in Kisumu, western Kenya, is mainly designed
"to find concrete solutions to the sophisticated and usually
armed smugglers".
</P>
<P>
The Kisumu meeting is a follow-up to a recommendation made
earlier in Arusha, northern Tanzania, by a technical committee
appointed last year to deal with the taxation and revenue
problems of the three countries.
</P>
<P>
Over the past several months, the committee have held meetings
on how to deal with the problems affecting the operations of the
revenue authorities in their respective countries.
</P>
<P>
In the past, individual countries in the east African region
have tried to tackle the problem of smuggling without much
success.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Jack Bigirwa, acting Assistant Commissioner
in the Uganda Revenue Authority, as saying that "we realize that
no country can stop smuggling individually."
</P>
<P>
As a land-locked country, Uganda is worst affected by the
smugglers' activities. Besides the border posts at Malaba and
Busia, smuggling is rife at other points on Lake Victoria,
especially at Gaba landing site, six kilometers east of Kampala,
and Kasenyi in Entebbe.
</P>
<P>
However, investors in Uganda argued that unless taxes in the
east African region are harmonized, meetings like the Kisumu one
would not achieve much. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
