<HEADLINE> Sinn Fein, Britain Hold First Talks Since Truce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Senior officials of Sinn Fein, the
political wing of the Irish Republican Army (IRA), held their
first talks with British officials today since the IRA called for
a ceasefire a week ago.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein's vice-president Pat Doherty headed the delegation to
meet government officials in Belfast to discuss Northern Ireland
peace process and the substantive multi-party peace talks slated
for mid-September.
</P>
<P>
The delegation also planned to meet former U.S. Senator George
Mitchell, who is chairing the slow-moving negotiations between
pro-British unionists and Irish nationalists, local reports said.
</P>
<P>
The IRA, which has waged a military war against the British
rule of Northern Ireland over the past 28 years, declared a truce
a week ago, allowing Sinn Fein to gain a seat in the September
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
To date, there have been no IRA attacks although British
security forces and the armed 12,000-strong Northern Ireland
police remain on the alert against violence by Irish republicans
or their Protestant pro-British loyalist foes.
</P>
<P>
The pro-British Protestant unionist parties, however, voted
against Anglo-Irish plans to seek "parallel decommissioning" of
IRA arms during the negotiations, which made a setback to the
government's arms surrender plan.
</P>
<P>
The vote will be discussed when Britain's Northern Ireland
Secretary Mo Mowlam and Irish Foreign Minister Ray Burke meet in
Dublin on Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
