<HEADLINE> China Holds Environmental Protection Workshops for Mayors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIDAIHE, July 28 (Xinhua) -- China's first mayors' workshop on
environmental protection ended here today after nine days of
discussion and brainstorming meant to improve local authorities'
environmental awareness and their ability to make effective
environmental policy.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was sponsored by the Organization Department of the
Communist Party of China (CPC) Central Committee and the State
Bureau of Environmental Protection (SBEP) and supported by the
World Wide Fund For Nature (WWF).
</P>
<P>
Experts from the SBEP, the WWF, Beijing University, the Wetland
International and the United Nations Industrial Development
Organization briefed the local policy-makers on sustainable
development strategies, the country's environment situation,
environmental protection plans, laws and regulations, as well as
methods of water pollution control in the Huaihe River, Haihe
River and Liaohe River valleys.
</P>
<P>
Mayors from about 20 cities, mainly located in the three river
valleys, attended the workshop and exchanged their experience in
protecting the environment.
</P>
<P>
The water pollution control in the three river valleys has been
regarded as the country's priority in environmental protection
during the Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000).
</P>
<P>
The State Council has stipulated that all the polluting sources
in the Huaihe River valley should meet pollutant emission
standards by the end of this year, or they will be forced to stop
production.
</P>
<P>
Sources said workshops of this kind will be held for other
mayors and one for governors has also been planned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
