<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Issues Tax Rules on Land, Housing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng earlier
this month signed a set of provisional rules on land and housing
taxes, the overseas edition of the People's Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
Taxes will be levied on taxable recipients of land or housing
rights transfers at a rate of three to five percent, according to
the rules, effective as of October 1.
</P>
<P>
The changes in land and housing rights include the leasing of
the use right of the state-owned land, the transfer of the land
use right, the purchasing and selling of housing, the granting of
housing, and the exchange of housing, the rules stipulate.
</P>
<P>
Each province, autonomous region and municipality has the right
to set, in accordance with its own situation, the tax rate within
the officially-fixed range of three to five percent, the rules say.
</P>
<P>
Tax reductions and exemptions can be extended in some special
cases, such as for urban residents who are exempted from the tax
for their first purchase of public housing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
