<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundi Rivals Agree on Another Peace Talk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The Burundi parties, which
attended peace talks in Rome last March, are planning fresh
negotiations on peace in Arusha, northern Tanzania, local press
said today.
</P>
<P>
The latest issue of the Nairobi-based weekly, The East
African, said that the Arusha talks would be under the auspices
of Julius Nyerere, former president of Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Felix Mosha, spokesman of Nyerere, said that the talks would
be held in mid-August and the exact date would be announced
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that Nyerere would like the meeting to be
"very carefully handled to avoid interference with the peace
process itself."
</P>
<P>
The Burundi FRODEBU party, which opposed the Rome talks on
ground that they closed the doors to many other Burundi parties,
said that it favors the Nyerere initiative.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome all peace talks under mediation of Mwalimu
Nyerere," said Simba Rushatsi, a spokesman for the exiled FRODEBU
president, Jean Minani.
</P>
<P>
The Chairman of the People's Reconciliation Party (PRP),
Mathias Hitimana, is on his way to Arusha from Brussels for the
talks, a close relative said in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
The National Party for Reforms (PARENA), which is led by
former Burundi President Jean-Baptiste Bagaza, will send a
delegate to Arusha, but Bagaza himself will not attend the talks
as he is not allowed to travel abroad.
</P>
<P>
A faction of the Tutsi-majority party of the Union Pour le
Progress Natinale (UPRONA), is expected to attend the Arusha
conference, but the other UPRONA faction, is unlikely to go to
Arusha, according to an informed source.
</P>
<P>
The Rome talks last March were attended by representatives
from the Burundi government, the National Council for the Defense
of Democracy (CNDD), the largest Hutu movement, and the
mediators.
</P>
<P>
The Rome talks were described by CNDD leader Jerome Ndiho, as
mainly aimed at signing a cease-fire, which provided a "better
atmosphere for the political talks in Arusha to take place."
</P>
<P>
Ndiho's fighting movement of CNDD signed a framework agreement
in Rome on the basis of negotiations with the rival
representatives of Burundi President Major Pierre Buyoya who
assumed power after a coup a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Though a small country in Africa, political climate in Burundi
has been plagued by racial and political confrontations, with
bloodshed and military coups in the passing decades.
</P>
<P>
The conflicts between the majority Hutu and minority Tutsi
have dominated the political instability in the country. Hutu
takes up about 83 percent of the country's population, while
Tutsi has about 16 percent of the population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
