<HEADLINE> Ramos Lays Down Economic Strategy for Last Year in Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
today made his last state-of-the-nation address, calling for the
two chambers of Congress to pass a number of strategic bills to
help the country pole-vault into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
In his farewell message to the Congress here, he said he would
not be a lame duck president during the last 11 months of his term
which will expire next June. He reiterated that he would not seek
a second term.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the Philippines will be highly competitive in the
next century, Ramos asked the Congress to pass some pending bills
such as the remaining components of the Comprehensive Tax Reform
Program, Social Reform Agenda, the Electoral Reform Bill, the
Poverty Alleviation Act and other important economic measures.
</P>
<P>
Ramos stressed that one of his government's top priorities in
the remaining period is the modernization of the country's
agriculture and industry.
</P>
<P>
"To spur the development of agriculture and industry, this
Congress must now pass bills pending since 1995 that provide for
more funds for irrigation, agrarian reform and more electric power
from renewable indigenous resources," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Congress should also support the fisheries
sector, mandate the efficient allocation of land for agriculture
and industry and encourage the development of appropriate
technology.
</P>
<P>
On the financial situation of the country, Ramos said the
recent depreciation of the peso might be a blessing because the
country was given an opportunity to enhance the competitiveness of
the peso.
</P>
<P>
The depreciation of the peso will not only conserve the
country's foreign exchange reserves and increase the real incomes
of exports and tourism-related industries, but also reduce trade
deficit and create more jobs, he said.
</P>
<P>
In the same speech, Ramos also enumerated the achievements of
his administration for the past five years.
</P>
<P>
During the period under review, the Philippines made a
spectacular economic turnaround from an almost zero growth in 1992
to a solid 6.8 percent in 1996, he said.
</P>
<P>
Over the same period, he added, the Filipino's per capita
income grew from 840 U.S. dollars to 1,250 dollars and the exports
rose from a 4.3 percent growth to a 23.9 percent while the
inflation lowered from 18.7 percent to 4.6 percent and the poverty
rate declined to 35 percent from 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
Ramos also said that in 1996 alone, the government created some
1.5 million jobs, reducing the nation's unemployment rate from 9.8
percent to 8.6 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
