<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The following are Business briefs
from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan`s Red Sea port of Aqaba will soon halve its
loading charges on container cargo exports to boost sales of
local goods in outside markets and help attract more regional
business.
</P>
<P>
The move applies to all container traffic of Jordanian and
non-Jordanian origins exported via Aqaba and is expected to
come into effect early next month after it is published in
the Official Gazatte, semi-official Jordan Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
But it excludes empty containers and bulk cargo exported
under bilateral protocols such as the country`s main foreign
currency earners potash and phosphate cargo mostly sold to
traditional markets under long-term supply deals.
</P>
<P>
The recommendations from the Aqaba Port Authority has already
won cabinet approval.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Sudan have agreed to hold a barter deal
worth 100 million Egyptian pounds (29.4 million U.S. dollars), the
Egyptian Gazette reported today.
</P>
<P>
The final agreement will be signed here in early August,
according to Chairman of the General Company for Trade and
Chemicals Mohamed el-Sheikh.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, a group of Sudanese commercial firms will
supply Egypt with some kinds of cotton and sesame.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian side will export to Sudan jeep vehicles
manufactured by the Arab Industrialization Organization, tractors
and food products.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey's largest company Koc Group plans to
establish an automotive factory in Samarkand, Uzbekistan as a
joint venture with the Uzbek government.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Daily News today quoted Hasan Bengu, general
director of the Koc Group's foreign trade firm Ram, as
saying that the factory would cost 75 million U.S. dollars and
produce minibus, midi-buses and trucks with an overall capacity
of 3,000 vehicles per year.
</P>
<P>
Bengu said that half of the investment will come from the
Koc Group and the other half from the Uzbek state.
</P>
<P>
He said that they would export the cars to neighboring
Central Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Qatar plans to increase its refining oil output
capacity by 70 percent to 137,000 barrels per day (bpd) by the
year of 2000, according to an official report.
</P>
<P>
The expansion plans comprise the construction of a refinery
with a capacity of 27,000 bpd of condensate and a fractionator of
condensate with a production capacity of 30,000 bpd, according to
an annual report released by Qatari General Petroleum Corporation
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The cost of the expansion project is estimated at 550 million
U.S. dollars, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Qatar currently produces 80,000 bpd of refinery oil, the report
said. 
</P>
