<HEADLINE> Philippine President Submitting Proposed 1998 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
today submitted to the House of Representatives his proposed 540.8
billion pesos (19.3 billion U.S. dollars) budget for 1998.
</P>
<P>
Ramos presented the proposed budget to House Speaker Jose de
Venecia after delivering his last State-of-the-Nation Address this
afternoon before a joint session of the bicameral Congress.
</P>
<P>
The proposed budget increased by 47 billion pesos (1.7 billion
dollars) from 493.5 billion pesos (17.6 billion dollars) for the
1997 budget.
</P>
<P>
De Venecia accepted the proposed budget and directed Rolando
Andaya, chairman of the House Appropriations Committee, to
immediately tackle it so as to expedite its approval.
</P>
<P>
The speaker described the 1998 budget as "modest", saying it is
necessary to continue the existing social and economic reforms of
the Ramos administration.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Education, Culture and Sports will receive
the largest share of the proposed national budget -- about 77
billion pesos (2.8 billion dollars). The Department of National
Defense follows with 51 billion pesos (1.8 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
According to Andaya, the House Committee on Appropriations will
start its public hearing on the proposed budget within "about two
weeks".  
</P>
