<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Sell Refineries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 28 (Xinhua) -- As a solution to its persistent
fuel scarcity, Nigeria may hand over two of its refineries to two
multinational oil companies, Shell and Mobil.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian Tribune reported today that a deal to this effect
is now being worked out between the Nigerian government and the
two companies.
</P>
<P>
The focus of the talks now is whether the deal will be based
on a partnership and who would have the controlling share.
</P>
<P>
With a daily production of about two million barrels of crude
oil, Nigeria is the largest oil producer in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The country, however, has been suffering from periodical fuel
shortages in the last few years, due to poor management and lack
of funds to keep its four refineries in good state.
</P>
<P>
Ironically, Nigeria has been importing refined oil products
from Cote d'Ivoire, whose only refinery, a privately owned
business, depends on Nigeria for supply of crude oil.
</P>
<P>
The government's new approach is a realization that
privatization might be the only solution before it gets rid of
fuel scarcity for good, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The government is also considering increasing the prices of
petroleum products and cancel the subsidies so that privatized
refineries can run on commercial bases, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
