<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao To Make 31.6 Million Dollars by Selling Stamps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Macao is making a fortune by selling
stamps as the government is expected to gain 250 million patacas
(about 31.6 million U.S. dollars) from stamp-issuing, more than
eight times the amount gained last year.
</P>
<P>
Carlos Roldao Lopes, director of the Macao Posts and
Telecommunications Office, said in a press conference here today
that all nine sets of stamps issued so far this year have been
basically sold out, making a total of 160 million patacas (about
20.25 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The amount of revenue is expected to go further to 250 million
patacas by the year end after another four sets of stamps are
issued. The 10th set of stamps, featuring Macao verandas, will
meet collectors Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that the office made a total of 35
million patacas (about 4.43 million U.S. dollars) by selling
stamps last year, up 75 percent from 1995.
</P>
<P>
The demand for Macao stamps surged late last year, following a
similar trend in the demand of Hong Kong stamps. The office had
planned to increase this year's amount of stamps by 20 percent,
but it turned out to be nearly 10 times for each set of stamps
issued this year.
</P>
<P>
While the amount of each set of stamps issued last year stood
between 200,000 to 300,000 pieces, it has skyrocketed to two
million pieces this year.
</P>
<P>
Lopes said that Macao stamps featuring traditional Chinese
culture are most popular among collectors. Marketeers sell them
several times the face value to collectors.
</P>
<P>
The office will begin accepting orders for next year's stamps.
It plans to accept more orders than the 8,000 it received for this
year's stamps. The number of order for 1995 was only 3,000.
</P>
<P>
"We will raise the amount of issues for each set of stamps if
we think it necessary," said the director. "But the increase will
be on a reasonable basis." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
