<HEADLINE> Unemployment Threatens S. African Trade Unions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 28 (Xinhua) -- South Africa trade unions
are likely to lose thousands of members as local businesses turn
to cut costs and enhance their competitiveness in the global
market, a trade union source said today.
</P>
<P>
According to industrial relations expert Jackie Kelly, total
trade union membership has dropped from 3.4 million in 1993 to
2.6 million.
</P>
<P>
The decline in trade union membership was due to the
widespread retrenchment and rationalization of companies, a trend
that would continue until there was a significant increase in
formal employment, he said.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's Central Statistical Service 1995 household
survey revealed that about one third of the 10.2 million workers
in the country belonged to trade unions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
