<HEADLINE> HK New Residential Mortgage Lending Down in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's new mortgage lending
slowed slightly in June but the amount of outstanding loans
continued the rapid growth of recent months, according to the
results of the latest monthly survey conducted by the Hong Kong
Monetary Authority (HKMA).
</P>
<P>
Gross new loans decreased during the month by two percent to
25.5 billion HK dollars (3.27 billion U.S. dollars). The average
size of new loans decreased to 1.88 million HK dollars (241,026
U.S. dollars) compared with 1.91 million HK dollars (244,872 U.S.
dollars) in May.
</P>
<P>
Repayment of loans also dropped in June. As a result, the
amount of outstanding loans increased 2.7 percent to 379.6 billion
HK dollars (48.67 billion U.S. dollars) in June, the same as the
growth in May.
</P>
<P>
New loans approved during the month rose 4.8 percent to 31.5
billion HK dollars (4.04 billion U.S. dollars), in line with the
revival of market activity in May after a relatively quiet month
in April. New loans approved but not yet drawn also rose to a
record high level of 20.4 billion HK dollars (2.62 billion U.S.
dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
