<HEADLINE> New Leader Elected for Lesotho's Ruling Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho's ruling Basotholand
Congress Party (BCP) has elected Molapo Qhobela as its new leader
at its annual conference, a report reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
Qhobela succeeds Prime Minister Ntsu Mokhehle, who established
his own party, the Lesotho Congress for Democracy, in early June
and declared a hand-overnd of government power to his newly formed
political party from the long-ruling BCP.
</P>
<P>
The BCP conference was held in compliance with a ruling by
Lesotho High Court, which ordered the BCP to hold a conference
before the end of July to elect a leader after several senior
members attempted unsuccessfully to oust Mokhehle early this
year.
</P>
<P>
Mokhehle's term of office in the BCP expired in January.
</P>
<P>
The BCP charged that Mokhehle's formation of the new party was
"an unashamed betrayal of the trust bestowed upon him by the
Lesotho electorate", and he was no longer the leader of the party
elected into National Assembly by the electorate.
</P>
<P>
The conference appealled to the country's Council of State
to call on Mohkehle to resign as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Lesotho government has started arrangements for
the establishment of an independent electoral commission to
conduct the next election scheduled for January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
