<HEADLINE> Liberia May Adopt US Dollar As National Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Liberia's President-elect Charles
Taylor is expected to get rid of the local currency and replace
it with the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
One of the main planks on which Taylor contested and won the
election as Liberia's post-war president was a promise to abolish
the national currency, a report reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
About 650 million Liberian dollars are said to be in
circulation currently, which the new government of Liberia
reportedly plans to buy up with about 15 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
One U.S. dollar is officially equivalent to one Liberian
dollar. It is reported the exchange rate became one U.S. dollar
to 70 Liberian dollars last week.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. dollar is highly patronized by businessmen in Liberia
apparently because of its universal usage. Users also complain
that the Liberian dollar is bulky.
</P>
<P>
Taylor won 75 percent of the votes cast during the country's
post-war election on July 19, taking the top seat he has fought
for since 1989.
He is scheduled to be sworn in on August 2 as president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
