<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Sees More Expatriate Arrivals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Expatriates, mainly Americans,
Britons and Filipinos, surged into Hong Kong in the six months
before the handover, official figures show.
</P>
<P>
The Immigration Department recorded a 13 percent increase in
foreign arrivals to 438,200 between the end of December and June
30.
</P>
<P>
A report in today's South China Morning Post said many of them
came to Hong Kong wishing to find a job in the booming economy.
Some took Hong Kong as a springboard to do business in China's
inland.
</P>
<P>
The largest rise was in the Filipino community--up 17,600 to
146,400. It is also the largest foreign group in Hong Kong, and
nearly all of its members work in households.
</P>
<P>
Another large rise was in the American community--up 18 percent
to 41,000.
</P>
<P>
Tim Hoffman, co-chairman of the American Chamber of Commerce
Human Resources Committee, said that a lot of U.S. companies were
setting up regional headquarters in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The British community increased 23 percent--the largest
increase in terms of percentage -- to 31,400.  
</P>
</TEXT>
