<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNG Soldiers Force Govt to Put Charges on Hold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Rebel soldiers of the Papua New
Guinean (PNG) military today held their commander under armed
arrest, forcing the government to put on hold charges against
soldiers involved in the mutiny of the Sandline mercenaries'
contract.
</P>
<P>
Newly-elected Prime Minister Bill Skate agreed to withhold the
charges until another inquiry into the contract was completed, the
Australian Associated Press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The overture came after a day of drama during which a key
Sandline mutineer, Major Walter Enuma, was freed from jail by
armed soldiers and military commander Brigadier General Leo Nuia
was placed under house arrest at Murray Barracks. He was later
released after a compromise was reached.
</P>
<P>
The compromise means former commander Jerry Singirok, who led
the rebellion against Sandline in March, would not be charged by
police with sedition tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Police said last week that they were preparing to arrest
Singirok when he returns from holiday in Australia.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers involved in today's operation sought a full
amnesty from the government over the mutiny.
</P>
<P>
However, after meeting with PNG Defense Force Chief of Staff
Colonel Eric Ani and Peter Donigi, Singirok's lawyer, this
afternoon, Skate said he could not legally grant a full amnesty.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said he had directed Police Commissioner Bob
Nenta and Attorney General Sao Gabi to withhold any charges until
an inquiry into the Sandline contract was completed.
</P>
<P>
An earlier inquiry into the 35 million U.S. dollar deal to use
foreign mercenaries to resolve Bougainville's secessionist crisis
in PNG cleared former prime minister Julius Chan and two senior
ministers of corruption allegations.
</P>
<P>
Acting Defense Minister Simon Kaumi met with military brass
late today to inform them of the Skate government's position.
</P>
<P>
He said part of the agreement was that the rebel soldiers
should free General Nuia from house arrest. Major Enuma reportedly
said tonight that General Nuia had been released.
</P>
<P>
The arrest of Major Enuma last Friday triggered today's swift
retribution by a hard core of soldiers loyal to him and Singirok.
</P>
<P>
Major Enuma headed an operation directed by Singirok to expel
the foreign mercenaries from PNG in March.  
</P>
</TEXT>
