<HEADLINE> 12 Heads of State Expected for Taylor's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Some 12 heads of state are expected
to attend the inauguration of Charles Taylor as president of
Liberia on August 2.
</P>
<P>
Among them are Nigeria's head of state General Sani Abacha who
is also current chairman of the Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) and Ghanaian President Jerry Rawlings.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders are reported to have played a key role in
resolving the Liberian crisis.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here today quoted sources in Monrovia, the
Liberian capital, as saying that arrangements are in top gear to
receive the heads of state for the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Taylor is said to have budgeted over four million U.S. Dollars
for his swearing-in ceremony.
</P>
<P>
It is reported Taylor has received about 500 seats imported
from abroad for the occasion. About 300 of them will be used by
dignitaries at the Executive Mansion while others will be used at
his private residence he plans to use as State House.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, three bullet-proof vehicles and 20 Triumph
motorcycles to be used by his out-riders have arrived.
</P>
<P>
As preparations are under full swing for the ceremony, west
African peace-keeping force (ECOMOG) has enjoined Liberians to
shun all acts that might be capable of disrupting the peace in
the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the force's Deputy Commander Brigadier General
Joe kwateng, ECOMOG has been intensifying efforts to "to ensure
that all the (hidden) arms are retrieved before we leave
Liberia".
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG is scheduled to withdraw six months after Liberia's new
government is put in place. But its chief, Major-General Victor
Malu said recently the stay of ECOMOG might be extended for the
training of Liberian army and police force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
