<HEADLINE> Gulf Countries Seeks Ban on Smoking on Planes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The Gulf Cooperation Council
(GCC) said it was seeking to ban smoking on all public transport
and domestic flights in all its six member countries.
</P>
<P>
The GCC general secretariat has also said it planned to ban
cigarette and tobacco advertising in all media in member states
which include Saudi Arabia, Oman, Qatar, Bahrain, Kuwait and the
United Arab Emirates(UAE), the daily Emirates News reported today.
</P>
<P>
Advertising executives in the Gulf have said the proposed
media ban would strike a powerful blow to the region's young
advertising sector and local economies.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf is considered a major cigarette market, with annual
imports in Saudi Arabia alone estimated at 800 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The steps are part of the GCC's efforts to curb smoking. Gulf
Arab states have already agreed to a gradual rise in cigarette
duties to 100 percent by 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
