<HEADLINE> 103 Muslim Rebels Surrender in Southern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 28 (Xinhua) -- A total of 103 members of the rebel
Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) recently surrendered to the
government forces in the southern Philippines, the military said
today.
</P>
<P>
Col. Nestor Castillo, chief of the Armed Forces' Civil
Relations Service, said the surrender of these rebels in Basilan
and Bukidnon provinces "shows the confidence of the rebels in the
current political leadership".
</P>
<P>
He said this also reflected the confidence these rebels had in
the government peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
Castillo assured these former MILF members that they would be
assisted properly and a livelihood program would be extended to
them soon.
</P>
<P>
Lt. Gen. Romeo Padiernos, chief of the Armed Forces' Southern
Command, said 38 rebels surrendered to the Army's 51st Infantry
Battalion in Tipo-Tipo town, Basilan.
</P>
<P>
In Bukidnon, 65 MILF rebels under Commander Balao Carnine
yielded to the Army's 8th Infantry Battalion in Maramag town after
long negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is a breakaway faction of the Moro National Liberation
Front (MNLF), which had forged a peace deal with the government
last September.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, which refused to be included in the MNLF-government
peace accord, began its exploratory talks with the government in
January. The two sides are expected to resume their much-delayed
sixth round of peace talks this week.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is currently the largest anti-government force in the
country with an estimated membership of 12,000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
