<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teenagers in Present Britain Have Healthier Way Of Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 28 (Xinhua) -- British teenagers have a healthier
way of life than those a decade ago, but a minority still drink
and smoke.
</P>
<P>
Exeter University Schools Health Education Unit found in a
survey that today's youth have a more balanced diet, watch less
television and pay more attention to personal hygiene than was the
case in 1986.
</P>
<P>
Fewer are drinking alcohol at 14 and 15, but those who do drink
drink heavily, shows the results of the survey conducted last year
and published today.
</P>
<P>
More teenagers visit their doctors regularly and brush their
teeth, but a smaller number of girls take physical exercise in
spite of an apparent concern about their weight, according to the
survey.
</P>
<P>
The message of health campaigners about diet appear to have had
some effect. More teenagers have breakfast than in 1986 when one
girl in five did not eat in the morning.
</P>
<P>
But about one girl in seven still has no lunch although the
proportion is lower now.
</P>
<P>
Both chips and crisps are less popular than they were a
decade ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
