<DOCNO> XIE19970728.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Output Increasing in Philippine Manufacturing Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 28 (Xinhua) -- A rebound by the Philippine
manufacturing sector continues as the Value of the Production
Index (VPI) in key enterprises slightly increased 0.5 percent to
438.2 in May from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
But on a month-on-month comparison, the VPI decreased in May
0.8 percent from the 441.9 recorded in April, according to the
data released by the National Statistics Office today.
</P>
<P>
Year-on-year increases were observed in nine out of the 16
major sectors led by electrical machinery and basic metals which
increased 33.5 percent and 22.3 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Other gainers included miscellaneous manufactures, furniture
and fixtures, tobacco and non-metallic mineral products, beverage,
wood and wood products and food manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
Significant decreases in the VPI were posted by textile and
petroleum products with 20.5 percent shares each to the negative
component of the manufacturing sector.
</P>
<P>
These figures were based on the results of the Survey of Key
Enterprises in Manufacturing, a regular monthly survey aimed to
provide flash indicators on the performance of key manufacturing
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the Volume of Production Index (VoPI) for
key manufacturing enterprises slightly decreased 0.5 percent from
148.1 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The VoPI is derived from the VPI and Producer's Price Index
(PPI) with 1992 as the base year. The index is a measure of change
in volume, net of inflation.
</P>
<P>
The VoPI for petroleum refineries dipped 17.3 percent, followed
by paper and paper products, textile, wearing apparel and
chemicals.
</P>
<P>
Year-on-year increases were observed in eight sectors, with
basic metals posting the biggest rise of 35 percent to 128.6.
</P>
<P>
Other sectors which posted double-digit VoPI growth were
electrical machinery, beverage, furniture and fixtures, and food
manufacturing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
