<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Weaker as Rate Cut Hopes Weigh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar finished
weaker today, as speculation over the Reserve Bank of Australia's
(RBA) next interest rate cut continued to weigh on the unit.
</P>
<P>
The local currency finished in Sydney at 73.55 U.S. cents, half
a cent lower from 74.06 cents last Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The market's going to sit in limbo until the Reserve Bank
meeting on August 5 unless we see some indication before then that
a cut will not be coming," said Stuart Moore, manager of foreign
exchange trading at St. George Bank.
</P>
<P>
Australian Federal Resources Minister Warwick Parer said today
the Australian dollar is currently at an attractive rate for the
mining industry and import manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
Parer told a Digger and Dealers Conference in Kalgoorlie in the
state of Western Australia that most people in the mining industry
are comfortable with the dollar as it sits now, after being very
uncomfortable when it was sitting up around 78 or 80 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was at 86.31 Japanese yen, from 86.35,
and at 1.3565 German marks, from 1.3633.  
</P>
</TEXT>
