<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Calls on ASEAN, EU to Strengthen Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Singapore today urged the ASEAN
(Association of Southeast Asian Nations) and European Union (EU)
to work out practical ways to strengthen their relations.
</P>
<P>
Local television reported that Singapore Foreign Minister S.
Jayakumar made the call when meeting Singapore local media today.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the recent expansion of ASEAN, Jayakumar said
that it brought a new set of challenges for both the nine-member
grouping and the EU. The ASEAN now comprises of Indonesia,
Malaysia, Thailand, the Philippines, Singapore, Brunei, Vietnam,
Myanmar and Laos.
</P>
<P>
How both side resolved these challenges to their mutual
advantage would be a test of maturity, wisdom and political
judgment, he said.
</P>
<P>
In this connection, he urged both sides to take a flexible and
pragmatic approach that has served ASEAN and the EU well and work
out practical ways to intensify the relationship, while managing
differences.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore minister stressed that as the ASEAN countries
took off, they presented the EU countries with enormous investment
opportunities. In the next decade, ASEAN countries will embark on
numerous infrastructure projects like the Mekong Basin Development
Cooperation, he added.
</P>
<P>
European technology could play a major role in this area, he
said, adding that ASEAN is uniquely placed to serve as a gateway
for the flow of trade and investment between Europe and Asia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
