<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Philippines Satisfied with Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PETALING JAYA, Malaysia, July 28 (Xinhua) -- China and the
Philippines today expressed their satisfaction for the trend of
development of their bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting here today, Chinese Vice Premier and Foreign
Minister Qian Qichen and Philippine Foreign Secretary Domingo
Siazon were also satisfied with their two countries' cooperation
in multilateral forums such as the Asia-Pacific Economic
Cooperation and the ASEAN Regional Forum, a Chinese Foreign
Ministry spokesman told reporters after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Qian pointed out that during Chinese President Jiang Zemin's
state visit to the Philippines last November, leaders of the two
countries reached the consensus that China and the Philippines
should develop 21st century-oriented relations of
good-neighborliness and mutual trust, thus giving a strong impetus
to the development of Sino-Philippine ties.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed thanks to Philippine President Fidel Ramos
and the Philippine government for their congratulations extended
to China on Hong Kong's return to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Siazon said the Philippines is enthusiastic about further
boosting its ties with China.
</P>
<P>
He noted that trade and investment between the two countries
have been increasing rapidly and great potential exists for
setting up joint ventures and carrying out cooperation in civil
aviation.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief that increasing economic cooperation
and trade between the two countries are of great importance for
their long-term relationship and friendship.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Qian noted that the two countries should set
store by their friendly relations and cautiously handle the
differences between them.
</P>
<P>
They could set aside the problems that can not be solved at the
moment and prevent them from interfering with their relations as a
whole, he said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Secretary Siazon agreed, saying that the two sides
should act this way.
</P>
<P>
Both Qian and Siazon were of the view that their countries
share the common goal of maintaining regional peace and stability
and they can continuously increase mutual trust and promote
cooperation in various fields.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers are here attending the ASEAN Post Ministerial
Conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
