<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Thai PM Seni Pramoj Passes Away </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Seni Pramoj, a former Thai prime
minister in the 1940s and 1970s, died today, at the age of 92,
according to local radio reports.
</P>
<P>
Seni died of heart and kidney failures.
</P>
<P>
Seni served as prime minister three times, each time briefly --
from September 1945 till January 1946, in January 1975, and from
April 1976 to October of the same year.
</P>
<P>
Seni was the elder brother of Kukrit Pramoj, who was also a
prime minister (from March 1975 to April 1976). During Kukrit's
premiership, Thailand and China established diplomatic relations
on July 1, 1975.
</P>
<P>
Kukrit died in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970728.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Scientists Use Computers to Simulate Evolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 28 (Xinhua) -- A team of British scientists have
used computers to simulate the evolution of life forms which could
explain how it works.
</P>
<P>
The simulation has revealed how a certain gene may have forced
dramatic changes in living things, such as the development of legs
from the fins of a fish, or bird wings from dinosaur legs,
according to a paper to be presented at the European Artificial
Life Conference in Brighton this week.
</P>
<P>
The simulation, conducted by Johnjoe McFadden and his
colleagues at the University of Surrey, provides a new explanation
for the puzzle that evolution seems to occur by fits and starts,
known as "punctuated equilibrium," while it is not a pattern of
gradual change. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
