<DOCNO> XIE19970728.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blue Chips Lead Australian Share Market Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Strong investment in blue chip
stocks, particularly the resources and bank sectors, pushed the
Australian share market higher today.
</P>
<P>
"Blue chips led the way with expectations of higher prices in
the foreseeable future," Peake Lands Kirwan senior broker Bill
Richmond said.
</P>
<P>
He said stronger commodity prices had helped the resources
sector, and there was a general confidence in the market.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries closed 32.6 points higher at 2723.8.
</P>
<P>
Diversified resources giant BHP rose 33 cents to 18.33
Australian dollars, mining giant WMC gained 13 cents to 7.87
Australian dollars and oil and gas explorer Woodside Petroleum was
up 31 cents to 11.46 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
MIM Holdings, which reported strong mining production
performances in its fourth quarter, was up 5 cents to 1.84
Australian dollars and mining giant Rio Tinto gained 10.3 cents to
21.35 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index was up 26.9 points at 1447.4 and the
all industrials index was up 41.9 at 4364.2.
</P>
<P>
Shares in Westpac Banking Corp., which had its 1.03 billion
U.S. dollar takeover bid for the Bank of Melbourne approved
Friday, gained 27 cents, or 3.28 percent, to 8.50 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Among the majors, Westpac Bank topped volume with a turnover of
5.71 million shares valued at 35.765 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Speculation continued about future takeovers in the banking
sector, fueling National Australian Bank's shares to rise 45 cents
to 19.73 Australian dollars and St. George Bank to gain 23 cents
to 8.76 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Bank of Australia, which reports its annual
results on August 12, slipped 1.4 cents to 16.48 Australian
dollars and ANZ Banking Group rose 2 cents to 10.50 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 308.52 million shares traded with a value
of 747.34 million Australian dollars (553.03 million U.S.
dollars), and rises of 624 outnumbered falls of 418.
</P>
<P>
The gold index was up 26.8 points at 1296.4.
</P>
<P>
Buoyed by the gold price in New York, trading in Sydney gold
bullion opened 2.80 U.S. dollars higher at 326.25 U.S. dollars an
ounce, dropped to 324.95 U.S. dollars at midday but recovered to
close at 325.70 U.S. dollars, down 55 U.S. cents.  
</P>
</TEXT>
