<HEADLINE> French Defense Minister to Visit Three African States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 28 (Xinhua) -- French Defense Minister Alain
Richard will visit Gabon, Chad and the Central African Republic
from Tuesday to Thursday, French Defense Ministry officials said
today.
</P>
<P>
Richard is expected to announce the closure of the Bouar
military base in the Central African Republic, which was until
recently in the grip of a military mutiny against President
Ange-Felix Patasse.
</P>
<P>
This is the first visit to Africa by a French defense minister
after the coming to power of the Socialist government, whose
leaders have been critical of France's traditional policy toward
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Local media said that France will withdraw its 1,400 troops
from the Central African Republic in a period from six months to
two years.
</P>
<P>
But, France is expected to keep its military deployment in Chad
and Gabon, where 550 French soldiers are permanently stationed
under defense cooperation treaties.
</P>
<P>
Agence France-Presse said that considering France's vital need
for oil supply, Gabon will be the most important leg of the visit
by Richard, who will hold talks with President Omar Bongo on
bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
France also has troop deployments in Senegal, Cote d'Ivoire and
Djibouti. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
