<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fighting Continues near Kabul, No Frontline Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Fighting between Afghan Islamic
Taliban militia and their rivals was continuing today north of the
capital city of Kabul, but no changes in frontlines have yet been
reported.
</P>
<P>
The fighting was going on about 15 to 20 kilometers north of
Khair Khana Pass, Kabul's northwestern gate, at the contested
village of Hossein Kot, said Afghan sources in Peshawar, a major
border city in northwestern Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The adjacent district center of Shakardara and its army base
called the Rocket Brigade were now under the control of forces
loyal to Ahmad Masood, former Afghan military chief, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
The echoing booms of long-range rockets and howitzers could be
clearly heard in Kabul, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Ten days ago, Masood's fighters, in a surprise infantry attack,
drove the Taliban back some 45 kilometers to establish new
frontlines well within artillery and rocket range of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in Vardak province to the southwest of Kabul,
fighting continued between the Taliban militia and Masood's Shiite
Hezb-e-Wahadt allies west of the provincial capital Maidanshar.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, the anti-Taliban alliance led mainly by Masood and
Uzbek warlord Abdul Malik sent an ultimatum to the Taliban,
demanding they pull out of Kabul in 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
The alliance warned in the ultimatum that if the Taliban failed
to meet the deadline, it would launch a three-pronged full-scale
assault against Taliban simultaneously from the west, north and
east side of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, who have controlled Kabul since last September,
have so far made no comment on the deadline set by the opposition
alliance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970728.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Will Act Against Currency Speculators: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad today said the government would take action
against rogue currency speculators but did not elaborate how.
</P>
<P>
"The government has got some ideas on what to do but obviously
we cannot just publish what we want to do as much as (American
financier George) Soros does not publish what he wants to do," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir made these remarks in response to questions by
reporters after he received foreign ministers of ASEAN dialogue
partners at the Prime Minister's Department here, according to the
Malaysian national news agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said the government's action would be based on its
perception. "What we can do depends on our perception. If we
perceive this as a criminal act, then we will act. If you think
that it's normal, than you don't act," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said he and the dialogue partners had a good discussion,
which almost centered on currencies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
