<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Sets Final Deadline for Illegal Egyptian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Jordan has set August 9 as a final
deadline for illegal Egyptian workers to obtain proper work
permits, or to leave.
</P>
<P>
The government is not planning to extend deadline again and
labor laws will dully and fully be in force as of August 10,
Jordanian Minister of Labor Saleh Khasawneh said in a statement
available today.
</P>
<P>
The ministry's measures are aimed at organizing the labor
force and easing unemployment in the country, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Ministry sources estimated that out of 230,000 Egyptians
working in Jordan, only 95,000 have corrected the irregularities
in their documentation and gotten legal work permits.
</P>
<P>
However, Egyptian Minister of Manpower and Immigration Ahmad
Ahmad al-Amawi earlier gave a higher number, saying 125,000
Egyptians have rectified their working permits in Jordan under a
bilateral cooperation agreement on labor reached last year.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian workers in Jordan were previously given three
months to obtain work permits starting from the beginning of March
this year, then the mandate was extended for three weeks. On July
9 it was further prolonged for another month.
</P>
<P>
The second extension of the mandate was in line with a decision
made by Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul Salam Majali during a
meeting in Cairo early this month of the Jordanian-Egyptian Higher
Committee.
</P>
<P>
According to unofficial figures, there are at least 300,000
non-Jordanian workers in Jordan and some 76 percent of them are
Egyptians.
</P>
<P>
About 30 percent of the Egyptian workers are employed in
agriculture sector and the rest in construction work, domestic
service, farming and a number of other services shunned by the
Jordanian nationals.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian government started to limit the number of
foreign laborers entering Jordan in 1996, in fear that the large
number of foreigners might impose threat to its own job seekers.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the government issued an order to close 16
occupations to non-Jordanians. The Ministry of Labor only issued
42,976 work permits to non-Jordanian workers, 55 percent less than
the figure of 94,333 in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
