<HEADLINE> Bulgarian President Arrives in Turkey for Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Bulgarian President Peter Stoyanov
arrived here today for a three-day official visit to Turkey aimed
at giving a new boost to relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
At the invitation of his Turkish counterpart Suleyman Demirel,
Stoyanov will, during his visit, hold talks with Turkish leaders
on bilateral relations and on finding ways to cooperate in the
struggle against international terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The presidents of the two countries are expected to discuss
the situation in the Balkans and the European Union (EU)
membership initiatives of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, a member state of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO), supported Bulgaria's application to join the
alliance at this month's Madrid summit, though Bulgaria was not
among the countries to join in the first wave of expansion.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's semi-official Anatolia News Agency recently quoted
Asen Agov, president of Bulgarian parliament's Foreign Policy and
European Integration Commission as saying that "Turkish investment
in Bulgaria is ridiculously low. Our country is in need of
investments to create new jobs."
</P>
<P>
Pointing out the negative effects stemming from the lack of
a cultural agreement between Turkey and Bulgaria, Agov said
that he hoped the two sides would also focus on cultural
affairs during Stoyanov's visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
