<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Claims to be on Right Track in Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 28 (Xinhua) -- In an appeal to its donors for a
continued aid to the country, Kenyan Finance Minister Musalia
Mudavadi said the government has been on the right track in
economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
The Nairobi-based daily papaer, "Kenya Times", today quoted
the minister as saying Sunday that Kenya enjoys reasonably warm
relations with international donors and the government is
currently holding amicable talks with donor agencies over
implementation of economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the Kenyan government has taken stern
measures to stamp out corruption, ensure efficiency and
accountability to maintain a stable economy.
</P>
<P>
The minister claimed that the government has so far undertaken
commendable measures in terms of liberalization and privatization
of the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
He cited the on-going restructuring of the Kenya Posts and
Tele-communications Corporation as one of the successful measures
in the privatization process of parastatal companies.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) blocked a 37
million U.S. Dollars loan to Kenya because of the High Court's
termination of the long-running 105 million Dollars Goldenberg
court case.
</P>
<P>
The 105 million Dollar fraud case involved millionaire
businessman Kamlesh Pattni and Former senior government officialsg.
</P>
<P>
The IMF last Thursday gave Kenya one week to show improvement
in economic reforms or risk losing the loan which had been agreed
upon.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that though the IMF had particularly raised
concern over the Goldenberg scandal, the matter was still in
court.
</P>
<P>
The IMF is seeking assurances that the Kenyan government is
taking concrete steps to recover the funds lost in the Goldenberg
and other financial scandals.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that if the government failed to satisfy
the IMF by Wednesday, Kenya would be deprived of the 37 million
Dollars second instalment of the three-year 220 million Dollars
Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility agreed on by both sides
in April last year.
</P>
<P>
Also affected are a 72 million Dollars Structural Adjustment
Credit and a 125 million loan for energy sector reform and power
projects from the World Bank, they added.
</P>
<P>
Mudavadi stressed that "we are making every effort to come to
an agreement with donors and under no circumstances should one
imagine an occurrence of a stalemate in the talks." 
</P>
</TEXT>
