<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Calls for Further Cooperation Among APEC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PETALING JAYA, Malaysia, July 28 (Xinhua) -- China said today
that members of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC)
should continue their cooperation under the principles of
diversity and flexibility.
</P>
<P>
In remarks made at a closed-door session of the ASEAN Post
Ministerial Conference here, Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign
Minister Qian Qichen said APEC has made substantive progress in
its cooperation process in recent years.
</P>
<P>
"This is inseparable from the APEC way, which is characterized
mainly by the principles of diversity and flexibility," as
confirmed by the APEC meetings in Subic, the Philippines, last
year, Qian was quoted by a Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"We maintain that at the APEC Informal Leadership Meeting this
year, the APEC way should be further improved so as to ensure
that APEC will continue to develop in a sound way in the future,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
On the liberalization of trade and investment, Qian noted that
as different members have different levels of economic
development, it is necessary to take into account the interests of
all the parties in the liberalization process and follow the
timetable set at the APEC meetings in Indonesia in 1994.
Under the timetable, negotiations for the elimination of trade
barriers in APEC member economies will start in the year 2000 and
be completed within 10 years in developed economies, 15 years in
newly-industrialized economies and by 2020 in developing
economies.
</P>
<P>
Qian also urged that the liberalization be carried out in
accordance with the principles of consensus through consultation
and voluntariness and on a flexible and gradual basis.
</P>
<P>
On economic and technical cooperation, the Chinese foreign
minister pointed out that it is in the interest of all members to
carry out such cooperation between APEC members.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need to establish a proper mechanism within
APEC for the cooperation process to achieve substantive progress.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Canada, the host of this year's APEC meetings,
would like the APEC leaders to concentrate on questions of
strengthening infrastructure construction and environmental
protection.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the focus of discussions on these matters
should be on cooperation in really solving the concrete problems
facing the developing members," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
On Hong Kong's activities in APEC, Qian said Hong Kong is now a
special administrative region of China and it should continue to
participate in APEC activities as an APEC member under the name of
Hong Kong, China.
</P>
<P>
He said China is to announce at this year's APEC meetings its
decision to host APEC meetings in 2001 and hoped that APEC members
will give their support for the decision.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970728.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "One Country, Two Systems" Sheds Light on Solving Taiwan Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The latest issue of "Outlook"
quotes a high-ranking Chinese official as saying that China's
resumption of sovereignty over Hong Kong should serve as a
reference for solving the Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
Tang Shubei, vice president of the Association for Relations
Across the Taiwan Straits (ARATS), said the principle of "one
country, two systems" sheds light on the solution of Taiwan issue
in four aspects:
</P>
<P>
Firstly, the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR)
enjoys a high degree of autonomy in accordance with the law and
the Hong Kong people have the right to govern Hong Kong. This,
when applied to Taiwan, means that Taiwan compatriots are to
become their own true masters after the reunification with the
motherland.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, the HKSAR continues with its capitalist system. The
practices applied in Hong Kong indicate that the rights and
interests of Taiwan compatriots will, likewise, be protected
following reunification with the Chinese mainland. The residents
of Taiwan have no need to worry about maintaining their present
way of life.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, the HKSAR is authorized by the central government
to handle a wide range of foreign affairs under the guidance of
the "one country, two systems" principle. Likewise, after
reunification, compatriots in Taiwan will be able to enjoy the
prestige in international affairs in its true sense together with
the people in Hong Kong and on the Chinese mainland.
</P>
<P>
Finally, reunification in accordance with "one country, two
systems" principle will enable Taiwan to take full advantage of
the material and human resources, and commercial market on the
mainland, while the Chinese mainland will be able to take full
advantage of Taiwan's capital resources and business expertise to
develop national economy.
</P>
<P>
Tang urged Taiwan authorities to refrain from preaching the
inapplicabiltiy of the "one country, two system"
principal. Instead, according to Tang, they should realistically
study the successful application of "one country, two systems" in
Hong Kong, and make correct decisions which will benefit the
people in Taiwan as well as the interests of the entire Chinese
nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
