<HEADLINE> Natural Gas Stations Mushroom in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 28 (Xinhua) -- Egypt is speeding up its plan to
set up natural gas fuelling stations nationwide as part of a
campaign to check air pollution, according to officials quoted in
today's Egyptian Gazette daily.
</P>
<P>
A natural gas refueling station was opened Friday in Dokki
district, Giza, the first in the northern Egyptian governorate
sitting on the densely-populated and heavily-polluted Nile Delta.
</P>
<P>
This is also one of the first natural gas refueling stations
set up outside the metropolises of Greater Cairo and Alexandria
where seven stations have been set up in initial plans.
</P>
<P>
The use of natural gas as a clean alternative for benzene would
reduce pollution by over 30 percent, Minister of Oil Hamdi
al-Banbi was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Natural gas also saves about 60 percent as fuel used by any
vehicle when compared with the conventional fuel, thus helping
direct petroleum production for exports, according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
Most of the envisaged projects will link consumption areas up
to natural gas pipelines and networks across Egypt, a country
which has a rich natural gas reserves of an estimated 330,000
billion cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
To harden in its environment drive, the government established
an independent ministry for environment in an efficiency-oriented
cabinet reshuffle early this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
