<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Cotton Shortage Predicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 28 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will have to
spend 111 million U.S. Dollars to import cotton a year toward the
end of the century, unless domestic cotton production is
dramatically increased, industrial sources have predicted,
</P>
<P>
South African cotton producers provided only 45 percent of the
domestic demand for cotton lint, General Manager of the Cotton
Board Hennie Bruwer said over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The Cotton Board said it had signed production contract for
almost 8,000 hectares with irrigation farmers, offering them a
further four percent increase in the contract prices.
</P>
<P>
This comes after a 9.1 percent price increase to 2.4 Rand (0.5
U.S. dollars) for a kilogram of standard grade seed cotton
earlier this year. 
</P>
