<HEADLINE> Israel Officially Apologizes to Jordan for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Israel has officially
apologized to Jordan for its undiplomatic actions taken by the
army last week, reported the state-run Israel Radio today.
</P>
<P>
Israeli soldiers detained a Jordanian diplomat at an army
roadblock near Maccabim between Jerusalem and Tel Aviv for five
hours without explaining why. His car was searched despite its
CD diplomatic plate.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Foreign Minister Fayez Tarawneh presented an
official complaint in Amman to the Israeli ambassador there over
the incident, saying that the diplomat was insulted by the
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
"We are speaking about an incident that can only be explained
by the fact that soldiers at roadblocks sometimes ignore their
orders on the treatment of diplomatic personnel," said Israeli
Foreign Ministry spokesman Aviv Shiron Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy is expected to apologize
for the incident to King Hussein of Jordan when they meet in
Amman Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Chief of General Staff Lt.-Gen. Amnon Lipkin-Shahak
has ordered head of the army Central Command Maj.-Gen. Uzi Dayan
to appoint an officer to investigate the incident, according to
an army spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The diplomatic incident has apparently demonstrated a low ebb
in the relations between Israel and Jordan. King Hussein has
openly blamed Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu for the
deep crisis in the peace process. Jordan is also unsatisfied
with the little progress in its economic cooperation with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel, for its part, is reportedly angry over the fact that
an Jordanian military court failed to give a death sentence to a
soldier who killed seven holiday-making Israeli school girls on
the Jordan River in March this year.
</P>
<P>
The court sentenced to life imprisonment with hard labor on
July 19 28-year-old Ahmad Mousa Dakamseh who killed the Israeli
girls at Baqoura in north Jordan valley.



28/07/97 7:11 GMT

