<HEADLINE> Quick Solution Urged for Beirut's Garbage Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Enraged by thousands of tonnes of
smelly garbage piling up next to their houses, residents of
Beirut's southern suburbs have threatened to relocate it in the
newly-built Sports City in the capital.
</P>
<P>
But Environment Minister Akram Shuhayyeb and other officials
were quick enough to promise a quick and efficient solution after
a crucial meeting this afternoon to prevent a health catastrophe
in the capital.
</P>
<P>
The pyramids of wastes have been growing at an average of 600
tonnes a day for the past nine days as the government closed two
dumps earlier this month in response to protests by local
residents.
</P>
<P>
In Hay Al-Sillom, heaps of waste have become the haunt of
rodents and insects, sending an unbearable stench into the air.
</P>
<P>
Along the Ouzai highway and in areas adjacent to the airport
road, smoke billowed from the green garbage bins as residents set
the trash alight to suppress the odour and reduce the size of the
heaps.
</P>
<P>
"If things continue as they are and the garbage remains on our
streets, there will be a revolt. We will collect all this waste
and throw it in the Sports City or on the airport road," said
Moussa Ghazi, a local vegetable vendor was quoted today in the
Daily Star as saying.
</P>
<P>
Standing amid a crowd of supporters, Ghazi said the garbage on
every street corner was spreading disease. "If we the people don't
act, the government won't move. We have spoken enough but they
don't listen."
</P>
<P>
The environment minister was quoted the newspaper as saying
that a location for a new separation plant has been agreed. But he
admitted that setting up the plant will take weeks.
</P>
<P>
He said he has discussed the issue with Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri, House Speaker Nabih Berri and representatives from
Hezbollah and Amal, the two Shiite groups which are most
influential in the southern suburbs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
