<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Hosts Science Fiction Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Beijing is currently hosting
China's first-ever high profile international science fiction
conference,
</P>
<P>
The China Science and Technology Association (CSTA) is
sponsoring the event designed to exhibit the nation's power of
imagination. CSTA Chairman Zhou Guangzhao noted that "the
grand meeting has attracted the world's most imaginative people."
</P>
<P>
Well over 100 astronauts, science fiction writers and
publishers from the United States, Japan, Russia, Australia and
China, including China's Hong Kong and Taiwan, are attending the
conference which carries the theme "Science Fiction, Peace and
Development".
</P>
<P>
Zhou quoted Einstein as saying that "imagination is more
important than knowledge". Zhou also pointed out that the most
influential technological innovations and inventions introduced
during the 20th century have evolved from the imaginative
descriptions presented by science fiction writers.
</P>
<P>
According to the well-known Chinese physicist, "The 21st
century excites our imaginations and fills us with
expectations. Conferees have entered the next century much earlier
than most people".
</P>
<P>
Unlike developed countries which use science fiction as a form
of entertainment, China considers the genre as a means spreading
scientific knowledge and educating the general public in order to
modernize the country.
</P>
<P>
While many Chinese officials firmly believe the genre inspires
young people to love science and promotes patriotism, some critics
say it will turn China into a future oriented nation.
</P>
<P>
However, various factors have contributed to the
underdevelopment of science fiction in China, including Confucian
philosophy which dictated that people concentrate on a secular
life rather than thinking about the future.
</P>
<P>
The central government call for promoting science amongst the
general public has created an upsurge in the popularity of science
fiction in recent years. "Science Fiction World", China's only
sci-fi magazine, now has the largest readership for any
publication of its kind.
</P>
<P>
"The world is changing more rapidly and indeed more profoundly
than ever before. While science drives change, science fiction
deals with the possible implications of change, helps us to deal
with changes which have already occurred and prepares us for
things yet to come," said conferee Elizabeth Anne Hull, a famous
science fiction from the United States.
</P>
<P>
Chinese sci-fi fan applauded Hull's remarks, with many
requesting the she pose for photographs.
</P>
<P>
The one-week meeting will move to Chengdu, the capital of
southwest China's Sichuan Province, following three days of
in-depth discussions on wide-ranging topics, including cyberspace,
the environment and space travel. The conference will also feature
sci-fi arts exhibitions and films. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
