<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-28 07:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan's Military Chief Endorses Sentence on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's military chief late Sunday
endorsed a military court verdict on July 19 sentencing a soldier
to life imprisonment for killing seven Israeli girls in March,
semi-official Jordan Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
With the endorsement by Chairman of the Joint Chief of Staff of
Jordanian Armed Forces Marshal Abdul Hafez Marei Kaabneh, the
verdict for Ahmad Mousa Dakamseh can no longer be appealed nor
contested in any court as stipulated by the Jordanian law.
</P>
<P>
The marshal ratified the verdict in accordance with Article 8
of the Military Penal Code of 1952, which grants him full
authority to endorse or reject a military court sentence, the
paper quoted military sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
Although the verdict can no longer be repealed in any court in
the future, King Hussein of Jordan, in his capacity as supreme
commander of the Jordan Armed Forces, is the only person
authorized by law to commute the sentence, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
Dakamseh will serve his life sentence with hard labor in a
civilian prison.
</P>
<P>
He shot dead seven Israeli school girls and wounded four others
including a teacher at Baqoura in northern Jordan Valley along the
Israeli-Jordanian border on March 13.
</P>
<P>
After a marathon trial, the court decided that the former
corporal was guilty of murder and sentenced him to life
imprisonment with hard labor in consideration of the fact that
he has been "mentally unstable."
</P>
<P>
After the killing in March, King Hussein of Jordan visited the
families of the victims and paid a great deal of money to the
family members.
</P>
<P>
Jordan signed its peace treaty with Israel in 1994, right after
Egypt conceived peace with the Jewish state. Jordan and Egypt
are now the only two countries in the Arab world that signed peace
agreements with Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
