<DOCNO> XIE19970728.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-28 07:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jewish Settlers More Defiant on Leaving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 28 (Xinhua)-- Over half of Jewish settlers in
West Bank would defy the government's decision to dismantle
settlements "under any circumstances," according to a poll
published today.
</P>
<P>
The poll, appeared on The Jerusalem Post, was conducted by the
Begin-Sadat Center for Strategic Studies at Bar-Ilan University on
511 Jewish settlers of 79 settlements in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
It revealed that 67 percent of the settlers would refuse
compensation in exchange for leaving the settlements.
</P>
<P>
The poll on "political views of Israeli settlers in West
Bank" also showed that 32 percent of the settlers believe the peace
process will crumble and the Israeli troops will retake
Palestinian population centers.
</P>
<P>
It was in contrast to the pessimism expressed by settlers 18
months ago. "The settler public believes that (Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin) Netanyahu will protect their interests in peace
talks. Settlers feel less threatened, and therefore are more
defiant in relating to eventualities in the peace process."
explained Professor Efraim Inbar, director of the center.
</P>
<P>
A similar poll was conducted in December 1995, when Israeli
Labor Party was in power. That poll found 22 percent of the
settlers feared that "most" of their settlements would be
dismantled over the next 5-10 years.
</P>
<P>
Today, 62 percent believe most of the settlements will be
annexed to Israel or remain as they are.
</P>
<P>
Whereas 20 percent of those polled in 1995 said they would
abide by a Knesset (parliament) decision to withdraw from the
settlements, the latest poll showed that figure had dropped to 14
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
