<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Arms Manufacturer Active in Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Denel, the South Africa
state-owned arms manufacturer, has confirmed that it was active
in the Middle East market, but declined to admit or deny any
contract had been signed.
</P>
<P>
Local daily the Citizen today quoted Denel spokesman George
Masoek as saying that Denel was having "fierce competition" with
Britain, France and the United States to sell arms to the
Mid-east countries.
</P>
<P>
"It is very difficult and we are up against major players
there," he said.
</P>
<P>
Denel was reportedly closing a deal with Kuwait for 100 G5
howitzers and G6 self-propelled howitzers. The deal with Kuwait
was worth for about 489 million U.S. dollars, according to
informed sources.
</P>
<P>
Denel's 155 mm howitzers are believed to be the most advanced
in the world, with a range of more than 40 km. The G5 and G6
cannons have firing range of almost 50 km.
</P>
<P>
Denel has prevented local press by court interdict from
publishing the name of the country or the financial structures of
the 1.5 billion U.S. dollars deal with another Middle East
country.
</P>
<P>
If the export deals were concluded, they would revive the
South African arms industry, which has been under pressure
following defense spending cutbacks.
</P>
<P>
The Rooivalk attack helicopter, made by Denel, has attracted
attention from the Middle East, including the United Arab
Emirates and Saudi Arabia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
