<HEADLINE> Lesotho Airways Sold to S. African Company </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The government-owned Lesotho
Airways Corporation has been sold to South Africa's air charter
company based in Johannesburg, Rossair, local press said today.
</P>
<P>
A Lesotho Airways source was quoted as saying that the two
sides were called to a meeting at the weekend at which they were
formally briefed about the sale and change of ownership from
August 1.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho Airways' three planes, one Fokker 27 and two Twin
Otters, are part of the 11.2 million Rand (about 2.5 million U.S.
Dollars) deal that will allow the new company to offer both
international (Johannesburg-Maseru) and domestic flights, said
the source.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Lesotho's privatization unit, a body responsible
for selling public companies to private buyers, said the
undertakings agreed to at the negotiations were still subject to
cabinet approval.
</P>
<P>
Both parties "agreed in principle" that the new company, Air
Lesotho, would register to take over operations of Lesotho
Airways Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho is a small land-locked mountain kingdom surrounded by
South Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
