<HEADLINE> African Bank to Aid Zimbabwe's Social Programs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 28 (Xinhua) -- President of the African
Development Bank (ADB) Omar Kabbar said his bank has committed
228 million U.S. Dollars for social and economic projects during
the next phase of Zimbabwe's reform program.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Harare-based daily, The Herald, at
the weekend, Kabbar said of this, 109 million U.S. Dollars will
be in support of the economic program, the Zimbabwe Program for
Social and Economic Transformation.
</P>
<P>
The remaining 119 million U.S. Dollars will be used to finance
water supply projects, an irrigation project, energy and other
service programs that will stimulate economic growth in the
private sector.
</P>
<P>
He said ADB in conjunction with the other co-financiers of the
economic reform program will meet with government officials soon
to discuss policy issues and identify other priority areas before
releasing the funds.
</P>
<P>
He said his bank was satisfied with the progress made in
bringing down the budget deficit and other measures announced at
last week's national budget by Zimbabwe's Minister of Finance
Herbert Murerwa to further reduce the deficit.
</P>
<P>
The budget deficit which at one time was 11 percent of the
gross domestic product, this year went down to below the targeted
8.5 percent to settle at 7.1 percent during the just-ended fiscal
year. 
</P>
