<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-28 08:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Puts Cyprus Issue on Dead-End Road: Denktas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Cypriot Leader Rauf
Denktas has said that the European Union's (EU) decision to open
accession talks with Cyprus has put the Cyprus issue on a
dead-end road.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with the Turkish Daily News
published here today, Denktas stressed that because of EU's
wrong attitude, neither he nor Cypriot President Glafkos Clerides
would continue the negotiations process.
</P>
<P>
He said Clerides had declared that if the EU postponed the
start of the accession talks because of Turkish Cypriot
objections, he would not attend the second round of the
U.N.-sponsored direct talks on Cyprus issue scheduled to be held
in Mondreux, Switzerland, in August.
</P>
<P>
The first round of the direct talks between Denktas and
Clerides was held near New York at the beginning of this month.
</P>
<P>
Northern Cyprus is of the opinion that if the accession talks
between the EU and Cyprus began, this would mark the end of the
intercommunal negotiation process, Denktas said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that any solution to the Cyprus problem should
encompass three fundamental issues: Protection of the special
relationship between Cyprus, Turkey and Greece; protection of the
domestic and external balances on which the republic was founded
in 1960; and the guarantee scheme.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus issue has remained unresolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkish troops landed and took over the
northern third in the wake of a failed Greek Cypriot coup
seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
More than 30,000 Turkish troops are stationed in the northern
part of the divided island to safeguard the security of the
Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot side declared unilaterally a breakaway
state "the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" in 1983, which
is only recognized by Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
