<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Get Certificates For Farm Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, July 28 (Xinhua) -- In northeast China's Liaoning
Province, farmers are required to take technical training courses
and be officially certified before they can engage in certain
types of farming.
</P>
<P>
Of the 110,000 trainees so far, 33,000 have received
certificates from local government departments.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning began the practice in 1995. The province now
stipulates that certified farmers have the right to contract large
farms and purchase wasteland for cultivation.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of local villagers have benefited from the policy,
which has helped improve the quality of local farmers and boosted
the popularization of farming technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
