<HEADLINE> North China Free Trade Zone Becomes Sealane for Inland Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The Free Trade Zone at Tianjin
Port, north China, had handled 7.14 billion US dollars worth of
imports and exports by the end of June since it began operation
five years ago.
</P>
<P>
Provinces and autonomous regions in the southwest and northwest
like Tibet and Xinjiang have spent more than five billion yuan on
foreign trade bases in the zone, according to San Xiangjun, the
zone's administrative committee director.
</P>
<P>
A special railway line was built in the zone to link it with
the second Eurasia Continental Bridge at Altay Pass in the
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Zone officials have even gone to other provinces to explain its
functions and favorable policies. As a result, nearly 1,000
enterprises have opened in the zone for foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
It handles 6,000 containers monthly, with more than 1,000 types
of goods, from north and northwest China and 102 countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
