<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profit Sharing System In China's Rural Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, July 28 (Xinhua) -- A profit-sharing system that has
been widely used in China's enterprise reforms is now being
expanded to rural areas for agriculture and has proven successful
in coastal Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
Fujian's Xiamen city used to have to bring in 70 percent of its
nonstaple food and vegetables from elsewhere, even though the city
government subsidized local food and vegetable companies with a
large amount of funds to ease the pressure.
</P>
<P>
Then, last year companies bought into Changtai County
businesses to establish pig farms and vegetable growing bases. As
a result, they have managed to form a production, processing and
sales network of more than 30,000 households. Farmers provide over
20,000 pigs, more than 20,000 tons of fresh milk, and 40,000 tons
of vegetables annually for Xiamen.
</P>
<P>
Workers, officials, and urban dwellers in Fujian's Zhaoan
County have developed some 1,600 ha of aquatic products bases in
rural areas, 70 percent of which were backed by local farmers,
with the two sides' earnings based on the share of investment.
</P>
<P>
In relatively more developed Longhai city, some 7,000 farmers
have purchase and sales contracts with farmers in poor areas, and
this system is more efficient than a single family could
expect. But it can only be tried on a trial base in more developed
rural areas, said an official with the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
