<HEADLINE> China's First Penguin Nestling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Zoo-keepers at the Shanghai Zoo
have spent the past three months and more, carefully nurturing
China's first Jackahh Penguin raised in an artificial incubation
environment.
</P>
<P>
The 36-day incubation period ended on June 1 with the nestling
emerging during a period of high humidity and heat considered to
be beyond the normal endurance levels of the species.
</P>
<P>
Zoo-keepers decided to separate the nestling from its parents in
order to lessen the possibility of bacterial infection. Careful
nurturing has helped to raise the nestling's weight from 81 grams
at birth to 1.6 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Osaka, Japan, a sister city of Shanghai, presented five pairs
of Jackahh Penguin, including the young nestling's parents, to the
zoo in June, 1996.
</P>
<P>
The natural habitat of Jackahh Penguin is found on offshore
African islands. The relatively small Jackahh are considered to be
one of the rarest of the world's 18 penguin subspecies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970728.0167 </DOCNO>
