<HEADLINE> China Committed to Stronger Global Multilateral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PETALING JAYA, Malaysia, July 28 (Xinhua) -- China today
expressed its commitment to a stronger global multilateral
trading regime.
</P>
<P>
China's attitude toward regional trade and investment
liberalization has been both positive and realistic, Vice Premier
and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen said here today at the Post
Ministerial Conference of the 30th ASEAN Ministerial Meeting which
opened here this morning.
</P>
<P>
China is serious and responsible when it comes to fulfilling
its international commitments, Qian said. "Regrettably, till this
very day, China has still been excluded from the World Trade
Organization. An early solution to China's WTO membership not only
serves China's reform and opening up, but also helps strengthen
the global multilateral trading regime and advance economic and
trade cooperation in this region."
</P>
<P>
Qian said China's development and that of Asia and the world at
large are inter-related.
</P>
<P>
As the world's largest developing country, he said, "China is
dedicated to its economic development and improvement of its
people's life. In the meantime, it is also committed to peace and
prosperity in the region."
</P>
<P>
"China's stability and development has already become part and
parcel of global stability and development. And a stronger China
will contribute positively to durable peace and development in
the Asia- Pacific region and throughout the world," he pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
Qian stressed that China's economic and trade links with the
other Asian-Pacific countries and across the world have become
even closer, and its cooperation with them will come to a new
high.
</P>
<P>
He noted the development in the Asia-Pacific region in recent
years has continued to attract world attention.
</P>
<P>
He is optimistic that the prospect of the region's future
development continues to look good.  
</P>
