<HEADLINE> Indonesian Police Arrest 55 at Party Supporters Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JARKATA, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The police in Jakarta, capital of
Indonesia, Sunday arrested 55 supporters of the ousted leader of
the Indonesian Democratic Party (PDI) for staging a convoy in the
capital without permission.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Gories Mere, chief of the Jakarta police detective
unit, said today that the 55 were apprehended because the
organizers of the convoy had got no permit to stage the event.
</P>
<P>
Supporters of PDI former leader Megawati Soekarnoputri had
planned to hold a flower-scattering ceremony at the PDI
headquarters in central Jakarta to commemorate an incident on July
27 last year.
</P>
<P>
At least five people were killed and 23 are still missing in
the riot, according to the National Commission on Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
In the riot, triggered by the forceful takeover of PDI's
headquarters by supporters of Soerjadi who ousted Megawati in June
last year in a government-backed congress, rival protesters set
alight or vandalized dozens of offices, banks, shops and
government buildings.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of police and security personnel were on standby
Sunday as crowds flocked to the PDI headquarters to mark last
year's riot.
</P>
<P>
As the crowds grew, the area of the PDI headquarters was closed
and more security officials were deployed around nearby streets.
All shops in the area were closed.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday night, about 5,000 Megawati supporters held a mass
prayer at her residence in south Jakarta in commemoration of the
July 27 tragedy. No disturbances were reported.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 11 people were reportedly arrested on Sunday in
Yogyakarta, central Java, for organizing a protest forum. They
demanded that Soerjadi, the current PDI leader, be tried for
allegedly ordering the raid on the PDI headquarters and causing
the riot. 
</P>
</TEXT>
