<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka To Develop Industries In North </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Industrial Development
Board (IDB) is to invest 2.54 million U.S. dollars to promote
small and medium-sized industries in the Jaffna Peninsula, local
press reports said today.
</P>
<P>
The IDB is confident that with peace gaining ground in the
peninsula, it could help the people there to restart industries
with foreign aid following the devastation of the area due to the
ongoing ethnic war.
</P>
<P>
The Jaffna Peninsula was once the stronghold of the Tamil
rebels, who have been waging a 14-year war for a separate state in
the north and east of the country. Government troops recaptured
the Peninsula in May last year.
</P>
<P>
The reports said assistance to industrialists from small
businesses in the Jaffna Peninsula would help to generate
employment for the youth in the area.
</P>
<P>
The IDB has already carried out 144 training programs and
trained over 6,800 youth during the past 18 months, the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
The government is keen to develop the small and medium
industrial sector as industrial employment accounts for 53 percent
of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports, the IDB's plans to hold an Industrial
Exhibition on July 31 to provide a window for local products to
foreign industrialists.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition, which will run through to August 3, will
display a variety of items such as leather products, ceramic ware,
motor spares, furniture, handicraft, textiles, office equipment
machinery and components, the reports said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
