<HEADLINE> Tom Dolan Clocks World Best in 400-m Medley </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 27 (Xinhua) -- World and Olympic champion Tom
Dolan dominated the 400-meter individual medley Sunday by setting
this year's world best time of four minutes 17.13 seconds at the
U.S. swimming national championships in Nashville, Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
The 21-year-old Dolan holds the world record of 4:12.30 in the
400-meter individual medley.
</P>
<P>
Dolan, an asthmatic, has suffered from health problems since
1994.
</P>
<P>
Cristina Teuscher won the 200-meter freestyle in 2:01.00 while
the 18-year-old Kristy Kowal burst our to win the 100-meter
breaststroke in 1:08.80.
</P>
<P>
Amanda Beard, 15, the American record holder in the 100-meter
breaststroke, failed to reach the final merely by 1/100th of a
second.
</P>
<P>
Beard took silver medals both in the 100 and 200-meter
breaststroke and was a member of the 400-meter medley relay at the
1996 Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Timothy Siciliano won his second title by taking the 800-meter
freestyle in 8:02.83. However, the 800-meter is not a world
championships event. 
</P>
