<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Drafts Stress State Ownership of Minerals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Geology and
Mineral Resources has drafted provisional measures to help
implement new amendments to the Mineral Resources Law, "China
Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The amendments, which were approved by the National People's
Congress Standing Committee last August and became effective on
January 1 this year, stressed the State ownership of the country's
mineral resources. It also aims at meeting the need to transfer
mining rights.
</P>
<P>
The measures regulate the transfer of mining rights and
the registration work for the exploration and use of mineral
resources, the newspaper quoted Jiang Chengsong, vice-minister of
Geology and Mineral Resources, as saying.
</P>
<P>
The drafting of the measures has received suggestions from the
State Planning Commission, China National Petroleum Corporation,
China National Offshore Oil Corporation and China National Star
Petroleum Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The provisional measures will soon be issued after approval by
the State Council, said Jiang.
</P>
<P>
Relevant departments in Shandong, Henan, Jiangxi, Sichuan,
Fujian, Liaoning and Hubei provinces are also working out detailed
rules to implement the new amendments.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that his ministry has made progress in the
administration of mineral resource reserves. By May 31,
two-thirds of China's provinces and autonomous regions had
finished registration of mineral resource reserves of state-owned
mining enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Notable progress has been made toward the drafting of a
national program for mineral resources for 1996-2010 period. The
program, which aims at strengthening the state's macro control
over the mining industry, leaves oil and gas fields and uranium,
tungsten, tin, antimony and rare-earth metals mines in central
government's control.
</P>
<P>
The final draft of the program has been approved by the
Ministry and will be submitted to the State Council for final
approval, according to Jiang.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
