<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos to Deliver Last Address, Push for Major Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
will deliver his sixth and last state-of-the-nation address here
today before a joint session of the House of Representatives and
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
Ramos' speech is expected to give high priority to the
enactment of legislation vital to the implementation of the Social
Reform Agenda (SRA), which the president has been pushing for
since taking office in 1992, according to the local media.
</P>
<P>
Aside from the SRA-related bills, Ramos is also expected to
push for the passage of major bills needed to "pole-vault the
Philippines into the 21st century."
</P>
<P>
With the May 1998 elections only 10 months away, the president
will likewise call on the legislators to pass the much-delayed
bill enabling the computerization of the electoral system to
ensure honest, orderly and peaceful elections.
</P>
<P>
Ramos has repeatedly underscored the urgency of congressional
approval of the electoral reform measure in time for the 1998
elections.
</P>
<P>
Also likely to be included in the president's address are calls
for the congressional approval of an absentee voting bill and the
remaining components of the Comprehensive Tax Reform Program.
</P>
<P>
The endorsement of the absentee voting bill will pave the way
for millions of overseas Filipino workers to exercise their right
of suffrage.
</P>
<P>
Since this will be the last time that Ramos will be addressing
a joint session of congress, he is expected to sum up the gains
the country has achieved under his administration.
</P>
<P>
Today's occasion also marks the opening of the third regular
and final session of the 10th Congress.
</P>
<P>
Ramos has claimed on many occasions that he will not seek a
second term when his constitutional single six-year term expires
in June 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
