<HEADLINE> 41 Ethnic Armed Group Members Surrender in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 28 (Xinhua) -- A total of 41 members of the Kayin
National Union (KNU), the largest remaining anti-government ethnic
armed group in Myanmar, surrendered to the government in June, the
official daily The New Light of Myanmar reported today.
</P>
<P>
Those who surrendered in June included the latest turn-in group
of 21, who "traded their arms for peace" in the second half of the
month in the country's four military command areas and the
Tanintharyi division.
</P>
<P>
The KNU, one of the 16 ethnic armed groups in Myanmar, has been
active on the Myanmar-Thai border in armed opposition to the
government. It is also the last group which has not yet made peace
with the government although four rounds of peace talks have been
held.  
</P>
</TEXT>
