<DOCNO> XIE19970728.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Small Village A Global Model for the Good Life (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, July 28 (Xinhua) -- In a small remote village in east
China, tidy rows of two-story buildings line the streets, the Old
Folk's Association sets local sanitary standards, farmers receive
a steady salary, and no fighting has been reported among residents
for the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
Welcome to Tengtou, which was named one of the "Global 500"
model villages by the United Nations in 1993 and has done much in
the meantime to maintain its glowing international reputation.
</P>
<P>
The 810 villagers are proud of their now-fine ecological
environment, booming economy and high moral standards, and are
doing what's necessary to keep on living the good life.
</P>
<P>
Twenty years ago, the countryside outside the village in
Zhejiang Province was covered with 1,200 patches of rough,
flood-prone farmland. Now, the area is neatly gridded with some
200 tracts of farmland separated by irrigation ditches, over which
hang grape trellises. Alongside the farmland and next to
riverbanks are more than 4,000 orange trees.
</P>
<P>
A small part of the land to produce grain is managed by
individuals, the other 30 ha is run by six households. The farmers
turn in all the grain they grow in exchange for salaries. They may
be given awards if their grain production exceeds a certain quota.
</P>
<P>
In addition to helping to cultivate farmland, the village's
agriculture company deals with livestock breeding, gardening,
aquatic products, and fruit growing. Last year, the profit from
agriculture hit a high of 700,000 yuan (84,300 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Fu Jialiang, village chief for 38 years and head of the Village
Committee, led local farmers in the campaign to turn their
community around.
</P>
<P>
"In the beginning, we didn't know what the term 'ecological
environment' meant, but we did know what filthiness is," said Fu.
</P>
<P>
He said villagers decided to first get rid of "dirt and
disorder," then gradually moved on to environmental issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970728.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Small Village A Global Model for The Good Life (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Fourteen elderly people, all members of the Tengtou Old Folk's
Association, are the village's designated sanitation
watchdogs. Once a month, they make a door-to-door check of local
households in search of general sloppiness. Those homes which
aren't up to snuff get a "Not A Clean Home" sign posted on the
front door.
</P>
<P>
The Village Committee requires that all residents behave
appropriately toward each other, keep the environment clean,
uphold social morals and live harmoniously with their family
members.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 20 years, no reports of fighting among villagers
or other crimes have been recorded in the local books.
</P>
<P>
But beyond the idyllic image lies Tengtou's economic
backbone: 21 businesses, including seven overseas-funded ventures,
which are concentrated in three industrial zones covering 33 ha.
</P>
<P>
Garment manufacturing is the community's pillar industry. Other
best-selling products made in Tengtou include building materials,
artificial gemstones and electric appliances.
</P>
<P>
During the first half of the year, total industrial output
value of the village stood at 180 million yuan, with a pre-tax
profit of 13 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Six years ago, an environmental protection committee was set up
to oversee the village's environmental situation. Over the past
three years it has turned down 15 projects which were potential
polluters and might possibly have been hazardous to people's
health.
</P>
<P>
"To bring these projects into the village is equal to inviting
a wolf into your house," said Luo Zhengyao, who headed the
committee.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the per capita income of Tengtou villagers exceeded
7,000 yuan; the figure was only 300 yuan in 1980. In contrast, the
1996 net income of farmers in economically-booming Zhejiang
Province as a whole was 3,463 yuan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970728.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Small Village A Global Model for the Good Life (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Villagers are quick to point out that their crowning
achievements are the general prosperity and lack of crime. Fu
Jialiang attributes this to the willingness of local cadres to
help out and that all capable villagers are come to the aid of
others in need.
</P>
<P>
Shan Liangfa moved his family to Tengtou 12 years ago when they
were relocated from a reservoir area. Shan's legs are paralyzed
and his wife is mute. They have three sons and a daughter.
</P>
<P>
As soon as he arrived in the village, Shan was hired as a
sanitation worker and his children were recruited to work in the
village's enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"We can earn 15,000 yuan a year, and we are living a happy
life," Shan said in an interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Fu Jialiang says he's still aiming higher, and predicts the
quality of life for his fellow villagers will continue to improve.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the thriving local economy, Tengtou has spent several
million yuan to build a kindergarten, an elementary school, a
library, newspaper stands, a village history exhibition hall, and
a closed-circuit TV system.
</P>
<P>
Various experts are often invited to the village to give
lectures. At present, more than 13 percent of the workforce hold
college-equivalent diplomas.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few years, the little village has attracted a
large number of visitors from both at home and abroad, including
some leading government officials.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Premier Jiang Chunyun noted during his tour of
Tengtou last November that the village epitomizes the
future of China's countryside.
</P>
<P>
Following a visit to Tengtou in May, United Nations official
John R. Krummel said that the village sets a good example for the
world with its coordinated environmental and economic
achievements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970728.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Georgian FM Prefers Russian Withdrawal From Abkhazia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 27 (Xinhua) -- A mechanism should be created in
the conflict zone of Abkhazia to replace Russian peacekeepers
there, Georgian Foreign Minister Irakly Menagarishvili said today.
</P>
<P>
It is more expedient, Menagarishvili was quoted as saying by
reports from the Georgian capital of Tbilisi, to have the
peace-making mechanism than extending the peacekeepers' mandate.
</P>
<P>
In what he described at a press conference as his "personal
opinion," he said it is necessary to work out such a mechanism to
"exclude any possibility of the resumption of combat operations."
</P>
<P>
In a related development on Friday, Georgian President Eduard
Shevardnadze said the world community's opinion should be taken
into account in deciding the Russian force's presence in Abkhazia.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Georgia's parliament speaker Zurab Zhvaniya said
the country's leadership had not been in agreement on the issue
but a decision "is to be made in the few days to come." 
</P>
</TEXT>
