<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Project to Help China's Poor Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 28 (Xinhua) -- A sultry summer like this makes
the wind of benevolence under the wings of China's poor children
all the more gratifying.
</P>
<P>
A charity program -- Wind Beneath My Wings -- is calling or
donations from the international community, reported today's China
Daily.
</P>
<P>
The program, announced in Beijing on Saturday, is being
organized by the Expert Committee of China National Committee on
care for Children (CNCCC) and the Foundation for Underdeveloped
Regions in China (FURC).
</P>
<P>
The organizations will use donations to assist poor children.
The initiative will continue until August 26, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
On August 29, donors will receive certificates commemorating
their help.
</P>
<P>
One-third of China's 60 million poverty-stricken people are
children -- nine million under age four and with varying degrees
of disabilities.
</P>
<P>
Universal Furniture and Stanley Works initiated the project,
assisted by the Mcphees, members of Plan International, a
non-governmental organization aiding the poor.
</P>
<P>
CNCCC was formed in 1991, after the Chinese government
developed the National Program of Action for Child Development in
China.
</P>
<P>
CNCCC is a non-governmental organization comprised of senior
experts and professors. It has 400,000 grass-roots organizations
with 2.4 million members in 30 provinces and municipalities.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1989, FURC offers assistance and helps farmers
battle poverty. Projects include creation of arable land,
supporting animal husbandry, growing fruit trees and water-supply
improvement.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
