<HEADLINE> Germany, Poland to Join Hands to Fight Flooding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Germany and Poland have agreed to
cooperate more closely to fight the worst flooding for centuries
in central Europe as the situation there continue to deteriorate
over the weekend, German officials said.
</P>
<P>
Emergency rescue teams of the eastern German state of
Brandenburg were working round the clock to strengthen the
barriers along the Oder River on the German-Polish border as more
dikes collapsed on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In the German border town of Frankfurt-an-der-Oder, water level
of the Oder rose to a historic record of 6.57 meters during the
day, just centimeters below the top of the dikes. However, the
latest reports said that the situation there had started to
stabilize in the evening.
</P>
<P>
After another serious damage in the dikes at Oderbruch north of
Frankfurt-an-der-Oder, about 9,000 local residents were requested
to prepare for an evacuation Sunday evening. About 5,000 people
had already been evacuated from the region since Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In the area south of Frankfurt-an-der-Oder, where several
villages had already been flooded, another three villages were
threatened on Sunday after new dike bursts at two different
locations.
</P>
<P>
In the Polish town of Slubice across the river, floodwaters
also threatened to burst banks at any time. Local authorities had
asked some 2,000 people still remained there to leave immediately.
</P>
<P>
According to German Interior Minister Manfred Kanther, German
and Polish officials had agreed to cooperate more closely in
dealing with the disaster, including more information exchanges.
</P>
<P>
He also said from Monday, the German military would dispatch
their Tornado aircraft with special cameras on board to discover
trouble spots along the crisis area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
